<HEAD>`Sharpeville Six' To Be Executed Friday, Lawyer Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 5 grafs after 7th graf pvs, Theresa Ramashamola ...
UPDATING with British government, Amnesty asking hangings be called
off. Pick up 8th graf pvs, Dlamini's killing ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The `` Sharpeville Six,'' a group of blacks whose murder convictions have drawn protest at home and abroad, are scheduled to be hanged Friday, one of their lawyers said Monday. Attorney <PERSON> Prakash </PERSON> <PERSON> Diar </PERSON> said an appeal for clemency was denied and the five men and one woman were notified they will be executed Friday morning. The six were convicted in connection with the killing of black township councilor <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dlamini </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Sharpeville </LOCATION>, about 40 miles south of <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, on Sept. 3, 1984. Evidence at their trial showed the six were not among those who actually hacked and burned <PERSON> Dlamini </PERSON> to death. They were convicted under the doctrine of `` common purpose,'' which holds they were responsible for the killing by being part of the mob that gathered outside <PERSON> Dlamini </PERSON>'s home with the intent to kill him. Human rights groups and government officials, both in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and internationally, have called for clemency. <PERSON> Theresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramashamola </PERSON>, 26, is the only woman on death row in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> for what activists consider a politically motivated offense. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> government expressed hope Monday night that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> will call off the hangings. <PERSON> Lynda </PERSON> <PERSON> Chalker </PERSON>, minister of state at the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION>, `` Even at this late stage we sincerely and earnestly hope that the South African government will heed the united call of everyone for clemency in these cases.'' She said <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> backed a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> call for the sentences to be commuted. About 100 lawmakers of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> signed a statement expressing `` total condemnation'' of the planned executions. <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, the London-based human rights organization, appealed to South African President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> to spare the lives of the six. <PERSON> Dlamini </PERSON>'s killing came during riots which began a two-year outbreak of nationwide anti-apartheid protests that left more than 2,000 blacks dead. Black activists frequently targeted black township councilors, considering them collaborators with the white-led government. The <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> appealed to the government Monday to `` demonstrate good will to the people of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in particular and mankind at large by sparing the lives of the Sharpeville Six.'' The scheduled execution date is three days before the anniversary of the <LOCATION> Sharpeville </LOCATION> riots of March 21, 1960. Sixty-nine blacks were killed when police fired on peaceful protesters demonstrating against the pass laws, which required blacks to carry identification documents while in white areas. The laws have since been repealed. The 1960 shootings raised an international storm of protest. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
