<HEAD>Handicapped People Protest DOT Transportation Policies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 50 handicapped people demonstrated outside the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> on Monday to protest what they said are federal policies that result in inadequate mass transit services for disabled people. Some protestors chained themselves to the doors of the DOT headquarters and vowed to stay until officials agree to improve bus service for handicapped people. Members of Americans Disabled For Accessible Transportation -LRB- ADAPT -RRB- gathered from around the country to protest the department's decision to appeal a January ruling that transit agencies must provide services to the handicapped regardless of cost. In the ruling, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Katz </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> struck down a <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> regulation requiring the nation's transit authorities to spend no more than 3 percent of their budgets on the disabled. The demonstrators timed their protest to coincide with a three-day meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which represents local agencies that provide bus and subway service. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> attorney who represented ADAPT in the lawsuit, said the present system of allowing transit agencies to decide what services to provide to the handicapped `` gives individual states the option to discriminate.'' <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> said that in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, handicapped residents must phone five to seven days in advance to get an accessible bus to pick them up. `` They should be able to use the next bus coming along,'' <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> said. `` Many transit authorities simply do n't want funny-looking people on the bus with normal people.'' Transportation Secretary <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnley </PERSON> said Monday the department is `` fully committed to providing mass transportation to people with disabilities.''
