<SECOND>PM-Panama-Canal,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canal Operated Despite Unrest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALBOA, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>, still one of the hemisphere's most important pieces of real estate, has allowed ships to move between the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> without interruption through nine months of political unrest. Nearly 13,000 vessels a year avoid the long voyage around <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Horn </LOCATION>, the southern tip of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, by traveling 50 miles from sea to sea through the `` Big Ditch'' that opened in 1914. More than 140 million tons of cargo move through it every year. The <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> Canal Treaties signed in 1977 commit the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to turn over complete control of the canal and military installations to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> by midnight Dec. 31, 1999. Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, commander of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> and the man in charge in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, claims <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> wants to renege on the treaties and continue `` occupying'' the canal indefinitely. He says the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration is waging a smear campaign to try to replace him with an administration it can manipulate. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was indicted in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> last month on charges of involvement in smuggling Colombian cocaine into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Although the canal remains an emotional topic of debate, its strategic importance has declined in the past 30 years. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> McAuliffe </PERSON>, administrator of the <ORGANIZATION> Panama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, says that is because the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has improved and extended its military forces. `` During and after World War II, through the 1950s, the major port system was <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and sealift through the canal was about the only way to reinforce presence in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, but now there are major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> naval forces in both oceans and major ports on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` There is less of a need to transport capital ships through the canal, and airlift capacity has increased tremendously.'' Traffic through the canal brings the commission about $ 320 million a year in tolls. Supertankers and the largest bulk carriers are too big for the three sets of locks that raise and lower vessels 85 feet, but 93 percent of the world's ships can get through, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Wainio </PERSON>, chief of the commission's Economic and Marketing Division. `` The Panamax is still the world's most popular cargo shipbuilding design,'' he said, referring to the largest vessel the canal can handle. A Panamax vessel has a beam width of 106 feet. The locks are 110 feet wide. Nor is the canal concept outdated. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> began a study last year of the feasibility of building another. Its conclusions are expected in 1992 at the earliest. For the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the strategic value of what used to be the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> Canal Zone is enhanced by the presence of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, involving about 10,000 American soldiers and 20,000 dependents, which is responsible for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military operations in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. It operates half a dozen bases along the canal and has its headquarters in <LOCATION> Quarry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION>, adjacent to <LOCATION> Balboa </LOCATION>. During their long tenure, the Americans built replicas of their own towns. Communities of white wooden houses on tree-lined streets named in English still can be found in the 10-mile-wide area that had been the Canal Zone. <PERSON> McAuliffe </PERSON> said this week that day-to-day coordination between his commission and <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> port authorities is `` easy, fluid and very effective.'' This month, there had been several bomb threats, which he called `` an irritant,'' and the commision flew in large quantities of cash because of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s banking crisis to cover the paychecks of canal employees. The latest checks were handed out Monday. Under sanctions imposed last week, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration is withholding monthly payments to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> of about $ 6.6 million for canal operations and putting the money in escrow.
