<FIRST>r i PM-APArts:JewishExhibit     03-14 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Jewish Exhibit,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Important Private Collection of Jewish Art in Europe</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fifty years after the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> closed the world's first museum of Jewish art in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, a private exhibit of Jewish ritual objects has been drawing large crowds of visitors. Some 800 items displayed at the `` Judentum in <LOCATION> Wien </LOCATION>'' -LRB- `` Jews in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>'' -RRB- exhibit housed by the Museum of the History of <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> are all loans from a private Judaica collection, regarded by art historians as one the most important private collections of Jewish life. According to <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Berger </PERSON>, owner of the collection, most of the drawings, paintings, sculptures, medals, coins, manuscripts and handicraft on show were in danger of being destroyed or lost after <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>'s annexation by <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in 1938. <PERSON> Berger </PERSON>, a Viennese businessman who survived a Nazi concentration camp, pieced together his collection over years and this is the first time it has been shown in public. The exhibit displays mementoes of Jewish life from the early 18th century until present, focusing on <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> as an important center in the history of European Jewry. Museum officials said it is the first step toward opening a permanent Jewish museum here in the next two or three years. About 6,000 Jews live in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> today, compared with 200,000 who helped make this city a capital of science, culture and the arts before World War II. They included <PERSON> Sigmund </PERSON> <PERSON> Freud </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gustav </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahler </PERSON>, <PERSON> Stefan </PERSON> <PERSON> Zweig </PERSON>, <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Schoenberg </PERSON> and hundreds of others. Some 65,000 Austrian Jews perished in Nazi concentration and death camps during the war. The exhibit is divided into eight sections, including ritual objects and Hebrew writings, the Jewish year and life, the history of the Viennese Jews, Zionism, anti-semitism and persecution and Jewish contributions to art and culture. `` It's the first time that the most important private <ORGANIZATION> Judaica </ORGANIZATION> collection in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> is displayed for the Austrian public after the war,'' <PERSON> Karl-Albrecht </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON>, a curator who helped set up the display, said in an interview. By March 3, the exhibit had been visited by some 30,000 people. `` On Saturdays and Sundays we have up to 500 visitors a day,'' <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> said, adding that recently Austrian school authorities advised schools to come and see the exhibit as part of their history classes. More young Austrians gradually have been educated about the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> past and the Holocaust in the two years since the first disclosures that President <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> had covered up his wartime past as a German army lieutenant in the <LOCATION> Balkans </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> said the exhibit was planned before <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> became president. The most valuable objects displayed are a silver-and-gold torah crown made in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> in 1810 and a torah plaque made in 1806 of gold-covered silver. The oldest display is a torah curtain made around 1700 of red velvet laced with silver threads. <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> said the first Jewish Museum in the world opened in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> in 1895, with a very big collection of Jewish art. The <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> dismantled it in 1938. While some items were lost or destroyed, others were taken by the Germans to <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> where they planned to open a big anti-semitic Jewish museum. The museum never materialized but some objects have remained in the <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> Jewish Museum which opened after the war. Asked if the Austrians ever asked the Czechs to return the items held by the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> said they never did. `` It's difficult to prove what objects belonged to the Jewish <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION> as all catalog were destroyed during the war,'' he said.
</TEXT>
