<HEAD>Rudofsky, Architect and Social Commentator, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rudofsky </PERSON>, an architect and social commentator, has died at age 82. <PERSON> Rudofsky </PERSON> died of cancer Saturday at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> University </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>. He wrote on a variety of subjects, ranging from the relationship between the body and clothes to how streets are used in cities. <PERSON> Rudofsky </PERSON>'s books and museum exhibitions influenced not only architecture but fashion, interior design, urban planning and food. `` He was our most perceptive and outspoken critic of human habits and habitations,'' said the chief editor of <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Design </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Abercrombie </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rudofsky </PERSON> first made waves in 1944 with an exhibition at the Museum of Modern Art entitled `` Are Clothes Modern?'' The exhibition, which examined the incompatibility of the human body and clothing, showed one of his contributions to fashion, the `` <PERSON> Bernardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandal </PERSON>,'' a curved piece of leather with straps. Twenty years later, <PERSON> Rudofsky </PERSON> had an exhibit at the Museum of Modern Art called `` Architecture Without Architects'' on vernacular architecture _ the design of buildings built in societies, sometimes ancient or primitive, that he believed were without pretensions. <PERSON> Rudofsky </PERSON>, who was born and educated in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, received a master's degree in architecture and engineering and a doctorate in technical sciences at the <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. He practiced architecture for several years in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. He has lived in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> since 1935. His books included `` Streets for People,'' in which he exam