<HEAD>Gore Draws On Disparate Background To Appeal To Different Groups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Standing before an only mildly interested crowd at a county fair in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> last week, Democratic presidential candidate <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> introduced himself. `` I am the only active farmer in this race for president,'' he said, stirring as good an applause as he got for the rest of his speech. The 39-year-old Harvard-educated senator from <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, perpetually clad in a blue suit, could be accused of stretching it a bit with that statement. True, home is a modest farmhouse hard by the <LOCATION> Caney </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fork </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> at rural <LOCATION> Carthage </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, set amid the <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> family farm operation. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, though, has hardly made his living working its soil. But his statement, often repeated, is emblematic of <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> as a man of varying backgrounds and worlds who has so far been able to balance them all. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> made the leap to the top tier of Democratic presidential candidates last week in the Super Tuesday primaries. He won six states, five in the South plus <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, and accomplished his aim: to use the biggest ever regional primary to jump-start a presidential campaign. He faces the task now of backing up his claim of being more than a regional candidate. While he is competing in the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> primary Tuesday, his hope is to advance as the primaries move across the <PERSON> North </PERSON>, arguing that he is the white alternative to Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the delegate leader. He depicts <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> liberal who, if nominated, could cause another landslide Democratic loss. Now that the campaign has moved out of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> can be ex