> following the elderly <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> in 1960. Despite a voting record decidedly more liberal than some of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>'s other representatives, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> won election to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> overwhelmingly four years ago when Republican <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> declined to run again. Whenever a questioner challenge's <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s claim to be a moderate, or his credentials as a son of the South, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> recalls that 1984 election. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> won 61 percent of the vote, running ahead of even <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who got 58 percent of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>'s vote.
