<HEAD>Thieves Or Murderers: Salvadorans Slinging Mud In Election
Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 To judge from the vitriolic campaign, Salvadorans have a choice between thieves and murderers when they cast their ballots in legislative and municipal elections next Sunday. Tough campaigning has been common in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> in the years when civilian politics has prevailed over the exercise of power by force of arms. But this time around the denigration of opposing parties' candidates and institutions has eclipsed most attempts to inform the electorate of proposals for resolving this tiny Central American country's tremendous problems At stake are all 60 seats in the <ORGANIZATION> Legislative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> and the mayorships and councils of 262 municipalities nationwide. About 1.9 million of the country's 5 million people are eligible to vote. The governing <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> are expected to lose their majority in the assembly and such a defeat would turn President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>'s last year in office into an uphill climb. `` The election campaign is poisoning the country, deepening resentment and hate and putting even farther off the reconciliation of a divided people,'' said <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> <PERSON> Guillen </PERSON> in his column in <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prensa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grafica </LOCATION>, the nation's most widely read paper. Monsignor <PERSON> Gregorio </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosa </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON>, auxiliary bishop of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, said in his homily Sunday: `` We would like to be able to say that the politicians offer a clear alternative to the violent methods that affect innocent people. But the political forum has likewise been converted into a war of insults.'' The party expected to make the biggest gains is the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, or <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>, an ultra-rightist group. Prominent Christian Democrats have conceded they have little chance of retaining their majority. <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rey </PERSON> <PERSON> Prendes </PERSON>, the front-runner for the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> presidential nomination, predicted at a recent news conference that his party would lose eight of its current 33 seats in the assembly. Presidential elections are scheduled for next year. <PERSON> Rey </PERSON> <PERSON> Prendes </PERSON> attributed the decline to `` the natural erosion of support experienced by a party that governs in difficult times.'' <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> is suffering in its eighth year of a civil war that has killed about 65,000 people, displaced 500,000 and ravaged its economy. The leftist guerrilla alliance battling the U.S.-supported government has denounced the elections as a farce and declared the voting will not be allowed to proceed in the northern and eastern regions under rebel control. <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> receives more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid than any country in the Western hemisphere. Economic and military aid last year was more than $ 500 million. The military said last week it could guarantee voting in 244 of the 262 municipalities. Defense Minister Gen. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Vides </PERSON> <PERSON> Casanova </PERSON> said 40,000 troops will be deployed to guard against any guerrilla attempts to disrupt the voting. Eight parties _ all centrist or rightist _ are presenting candidates, but only three are competing nationwide. Left-of-center parties declined to participate, citing lack of security for their candidates. Rightist death squads killed several thousand leftist union and political activists in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> in the early 1980s. Human rights groups say the squads remain intact, and the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> recently denounced what it said was an increase in the number of politically motivated murders. Arena and its founder, retired army Maj. <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> d'Aubuisson </PERSON>, have been linked to the death squads since the party's formation in 1982. At a recent <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> campaign rally in <LOCATION> Panchimalco </LOCATION>, six miles south of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, speakers repeatedly referred to <PERSON> D'Aubuisson </PERSON>'s group as `` torturers'' and `` killers.'' Arena, for its part, calls the <ORGANIZATION> PDC </ORGANIZATION> _ the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s initials in <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> _ the party of the corrupt. Arena, which has 13 legislators in the current assembly, is not expected to win an outright majority. But most observers believe it will win almost as many seats as the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. That could leave the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conciliation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> _ the third group competing nationwide _ with the balance of power. The rightist <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conciliation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> was formed by the military and governed for nearly 20 years before a 1979 coup. It formed an alliance with <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> in the 1985 legislative elections. But the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conciliation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, in an effort to portray itself as moderate, eschewed the alliance this time around. `` Against the death squads and the thieves, <ORGANIZATION> PCN </ORGANIZATION>,'' has been its slogan in this campaign. The <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, which groups five rebel organizations, said in a communique last month: `` The country has lost its sovereignty -LRB- to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> -RRB- and democracy does not exist. Rather there is a new kind of military dictatorship with a civilian facade. Without independence, no election is legitimate.''
