<HEAD>Jackson Campaign Could Move Into Financial Big Leagues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> likes to say he has the `` poor campaign with a rich message,'' but he may have to alter that slogan a bit if his fund-raising trends continue. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s mail consultant <PERSON> Mal </PERSON> <PERSON> Warwick </PERSON> said that while <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is not in the league of other multi-million-dollar presidential contenders, the response to his mail solicitations is so overwhelming that <PERSON> Warwick </PERSON> has had to increase his 12-person money-counting staff to 30 over the past two months. It is too early to tell how <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s strong showing in the Super Tuesday states will affect his contributions, <ORGANIZATION> Warwick </ORGANIZATION> said. But he added, `` Money has been coming in so far ahead of projections that we are struggling to keep up with it.'' The mail results have grown steadily since last fall, when about $ 150,000 per month was coming in, said campaign treasurer <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Renzi </PERSON>. That increased to about $ 270,000 in January. And in February, the month when primaries and caucuses began, $ 400,000 of the $ 750,000 the campaign raised came in through the mail, <PERSON> Renzi </PERSON> said. `` We're starting to approach the time where we'll have the financial wherewithal to be more competitive,'' he said, adding that a good part of the money raised by mail is going back into the mail program to develop a bigger base of contributors. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> still has a long way to go to catch up with Democratic money leader <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who had raised some $ 15 million by the end of January, including federal matching funds, to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s $ 3.3 million <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has made much of the fact that he has done well despite being outspent by as much as 30 times in states where his opponents put on heavy media campaigns. But his sophisticated mail program is producing results that were unheard of in <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s 1984 campaign, when taking a collection at revival-style rallies was his most frequent fund-raising approach. <ORGANIZATION> Warwick </ORGANIZATION> runs a state-of-the-art direct mail and telemarketing operation, utilizing lists of names purchased from other mail soliciters to determine which categories of people would be most likely to give to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` We're using every technique in the book,'' he said, and sending mail to a broad spectrum of progressive Democrats. The mail includes everything from postcards to sophisticated packets and questionnaires through first-class mail. In addition to the mail, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s campaign chairman <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, influential speaker of the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> state assembly, said there will be a series of concerts to raise money in the weeks to come. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, one of the most successful fund-raisers in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> politics, also said this week he will try to extract $ 1 million from the state's `` bleeding hearts'' whom he said should be giving money to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Warwick </PERSON> said about one mailing per week goes out, ranging in size from 5,000 pieces to previous contributors, to 400,000 pieces in a search for new donors. `` The results we are obtaining are as strong as anything I've ever witnessed in all my time of direct mail fund-raising,'' <PERSON> Warwick </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Warwick </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, firm, <ORGANIZATION> Changing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, handled direct mail for the presidential campaign of <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> last year before <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> dropped out of the race the first time, and has several liberal organizations as clients. One `` Dear Fellow American Citizen'' letter from <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was sent to white liberal Democratics in affluent <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. In what the industry calls the `` involvement'' approach, it included an `` issues survey'' asking the reader's opinion on <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s key issues. Another mailing that went out after the Feb. 8 <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> caucuses highlighted <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s 8 percent showing in a state with a 1.4 percent black population as evidence that he has support outside the black community, contrary to what `` so called political experts'' had claimed. <ORGANIZATION> Warwick </ORGANIZATION> said that since names on his mailing lists are `` overwhelmingly non-black,'' white people obviously are contributing to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` For us to get the results we are getting means he has very substantial support among white mail donors,'' he said. <PERSON> Warwick </PERSON> would not be specific on the rate of return for the amount of mail sent out, but said it was `` much better'' than the 1 percent to 1.5 percent return that is typical for so-called prospecting mail, in which new donors are sought out.
