<HEAD>New Missile Installation Would Extend `Overrated' Threat</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Reports that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> may be planning to install Silkworm anti-ship missiles on a tiny island in the southern <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> add a new element to a much-publicized threat that some <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> naval officers say has been greatly overrated. Military sources in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said surveillance had detected evidence that crude missile launch pads were being built on <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Musa </PERSON>, an outcropping long used as a base for armed speedboat attacks on gulf shipping by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s Revolutionary Guards. The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said there was still no sign of the missiles being installed. Nor did they speculate on what purpose the Chinese-built weapons might serve if located there. But missiles on <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Musa </PERSON> would extend the so-called `` Silkworm envelope'' along <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s coast bordering the Strait of <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION> by about 100 miles, `` doubling the arc'' of the present threat, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> source said. It would put the missiles, which have a maximum range of 50 to 60 miles, within easy reach of the main shipping channel leading to and from the Hormuz passage, as well as a populated stretch of the Arab coast. Five of the seven <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> port cities _ <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sharjah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ajman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Umm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Al </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Qaiwain </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Ras </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Khaimah </PERSON> _ are 50 miles or less from <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Musa </PERSON>. Gulf-area diplomats and shipping executives expressed alarm early last year when it was disclosed that <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> was deploying mobile Silkworm batteries along the Hormuz, the only outlet from the oil-rich gulf to the open sea. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> was said to have successfully test-fired several of the missiles at an old ship's hulk. Subsequent reports have said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> possessed as many as 100 Silkworms, apparently supplied by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, although <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> has publicly denied the sales. Senior American officials made it clear from the outset that any Iranian use of the weapon would be met with swift retaliation. Then-Defense Secretary <PERSON> Caspar </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> said that while <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> did not contemplate `` pre-emptive strikes,'' even the activation of a Silkworm's target-tracking radar would be seen as a hostile act, to which the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> would respond. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s subsequent reluctance to even threaten to use the missiles in the strategic Hormuz has caused <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> naval officers to view the threat with increasing skepticism. The convoys of U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tankers continue to have protective air cover while passing through the `` envelope,'' but some warships now sail with crews at less than a full `` battle stations'' alert status, de rigeur when the operation began last July. `` Of course we ca n't rule the Silkworms out as a potential threat, but in my opinion it's been overrated _ right from the start,'' a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> intelligence officer said several months ago. Other American officers have said the Silkworms in the Hormuz are probably the least of their worries in sailing through the gulf. More imminent concerns include Iranian speedboats and most of all, another mistaken Iraqi air strike such as that which wrecked the missile frigate Stark, killing 37 Americans, last May 17. One senior officer said he would not discount the idea of some `` crazies'' firing a Silkworm in defiance of orders, but believed the danger from a planned attack was virtually nil. `` As long as we maintain our retaliatory assets in the <LOCATION> Arabian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, that is n't going to occur,'' he said, referring to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aircraft carrier _ currently the nuclear-powered Enterprise _ permanently stationed outside the gulf. `` The Iranians are n't about to fire one of those things -LRB- Silkworms -RRB- at a warship or a ship under navy escort. They know what would happen if they did. They'd be taken out in minutes,'' he said. Friday's report of Silkworm-related activity on <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Musa </PERSON> came just as the only U.S.-flagged ship ever hit by a Silkworm was sailing past the island. The 81,283-ton <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Isle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, one of the 11 Kuwait-owned tankers reflagged with the Stars and Stripes for protection from Iranian attack, was heading out of the gulf in a navy convoy. It was the first trip for the ship since it was devastated by a Silkworm last Oct. 16 while anchored at <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s main offshore oil terminal. That missile, and a handful of others launched from Iran-held territory in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Faw </LOCATION> <LOCATION> peninsula </LOCATION>, are the only ones that <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s forces are known to have fired. The Silkworm, officially designated HY-2 by the Chinese, is a variant of the 30-year-old Soviet Styx missile. The cumbersome, 20-foot-long projectile flies just above the water at subsonic speed, homing on its target by radar. Although the weapon is crude by modern standards, its 1,000-pound warhead can cause severe damage. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> naval officials called the hit on the <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Isle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> a lucky shot, but the tanker was out of service for nearly five months.
