<HEAD>Clarence Darrow Admirers Commemorate 50th Anniversay Of His Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Admirers of <PERSON> Clarence </PERSON> <PERSON> Darrow </PERSON> marked the 50th anniversary of the death of `` the attorney of the damned'' by tossing a wreath into the lagoon where his ashes are scattered and pledging to live by his example. About 100 people huddled together against the snow Sunday on a bridge in a park on <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s South Side. <PERSON> Darrow </PERSON>, a skeptic on matters of religion and the afterlife, said if there was anything to the spiritual world, he would return at 10 in the morning on each anniversary of his death, according to <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Despres </PERSON>, a former alderman of the 5th <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, where <PERSON> Darrow </PERSON> lived. For years after <PERSON> Darrow </PERSON>'s death, magicians and spiritualists gathered at the bridge to conjure up the lawyer's spirit _ but year after year they went away disappointed. Those gathered at the bridge departed with a renewed sense of commitment to the ideals <PERSON> Darrow </PERSON> stood for: justice and equality. `` For those of you who question life after death ... <PERSON> Clarence </PERSON> is here in spirit today as we commit ourselves to follow the example of his life,'' said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Prentice </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>. About a dozen attorneys, politicians, judges and ministers addressed the crowd in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, a few blocks from <PERSON> Darrow </PERSON>'s home In his 50 years as a lawyer, <PERSON> Darrow </PERSON> defended `` the preconvicted, the powerless, those damned before they had a chance to have a fair trial,'' said <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Kraus </PERSON>, a co-chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Clarence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Darrow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commemorative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. One of <PERSON> Darrow </PERSON>'s most famous clients was <LOCATIO