<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has quietly disbanded the group it set up more than two years ago to sell the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's widely criticized policy towards <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> `` </PERSON> <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> `` </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON>, the most recent director of the <ORGANIZATION> Working </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> And </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, said the office effectively closed at the end of 1987. The decision not to continue the office resulted in part because <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has waned as an issue attracting daily headlines in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON> said. `` By 1987 there were other issues,'' he said. `` There was the -LRB- Persian -RRB- Gulf, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> in general, the controversy involving <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>,'' he said. The office, which at one point had a staff of about 20, was created in late 1985 as the administration pursued its policy of `` constructive engagement,'' _ attempting to pressure the white government in <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> into eliminating racial segregation through diplomacy rather than sanctions. But <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> _ against the administration's will _ approved sanctions in 1986, thereby undercutting `` constructive engagement.'' House members are preparing to consider a measure later this month that would impose a full economic embargo on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON> said the working group did a good job explaining the department's <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> policy. `` We got out the message ... People were much better informed in 1987 than in 1985.'' When the group was set up, it was never intended to be a permanent fixture, he said. He said the working group's staff traveled to over 45 states and gave more than 1,000 speeches to civic and business groups and met with reporters and editors from television stations and newspapers. The group was modeled after the department's <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diplomacy </ORGANIZATION> for <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. That operation was also shut down.
