<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A young lawyer, who was once kidnapped because he campaigned against drugs, has been elected mayor of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> in the first mayoral elections in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s history. Security at the polls Sunday was tight throughout this country racked by violence from extremist political factions and from powerful narcotics traffickers. One of the alleged leaders of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s biggest drug organization even tried to run for city council in the town of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivas </PERSON> failed because Colombian law demands that candidates sign up in person. <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> is in jail in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, facing drug charges there and in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Pastrana </PERSON>, 34, the son of former President <PERSON> Misael </PERSON> <PERSON> Pastrana </PERSON>, became <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>'s mayor and will be one of the youngest men to take that important political post. Several <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> mayors have gone on to become president. <PERSON> Pastrana </PERSON> is a rising star in the <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, and his election represents a setback for President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON>'s governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Pastrana </PERSON> was the only <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> candidate for mayor in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>. The feuding <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> put up three candidates. Voters heeded <PERSON> Barco </PERSON>'s plea to fight bullets with ballots in the election, which was called as a concession to leftist guerrillas. For the past 169 years, the president, always from either the Liberal or Conservative parties, had appointed governors who in turn named mayors. There were 1,008 mayors elected Sunday. Colombians also elected city council, state assemblies and governing bodies for remote territories without sufficient population to become states. In the <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> race, <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Caicedo </PERSON>, a former president of the <ORGANIZATION> Colombian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Businessmen </ORGANIZATION>, came in second place. With about 50 percent of the vote in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> counted, <PERSON> Pastrana </PERSON> had 122,107 votes and <PERSON> Caicedo </PERSON> had 94,322, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elections </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said in a news release Sunday night. By late Sunday night the elections office said the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> had won 405 of the mayoral races, the Conservative Party 379 and the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Patriotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> 13. Coalition candidates representing several parties had won 104 mayoral posts, the elctions office said. <PERSON> Barco </PERSON>, in a speech televised nationwide Saturday night, said voting would be a way to reject the wave of violence that has swept <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. More than 1,700 people were killed in the past year in fighting between leftist guerrillas and government security forces and by right-wing death squads and drug traffickers. On Sunday, soldiers and police guarded voting places and patrolled cities and towns. The campaign was one of the bloodiest ever in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, with leftist guerrillas and right-wing death squads killing five mayoral candidates and 19 city council candidates. Hundreds of other political activists were slain. Leftist guerrillas kidnapped 14 mayors in the two weeks before the election. The rebels let them go after warning each to do more for the poor. <PERSON> Pastrana </PERSON>, who called for stronger action against the multibillion-dollar cocaine and marijuana trafficking in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, was kidnapped by drug traffickers in January. A week later, police acting on a tip, raided a farmhouse where he was held. <PERSON> Pastrana </PERSON> had not been harmed. Colombian officials sometimes pay with their lives for challenging drug traffickers, who are among the wealthiest men in the nation. One group, the <ORGANIZATION> Medillin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cartel </ORGANIZATION>, is said to be responsible for 80 percent of the cocaine smuggled into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> is charged in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> with being one of its leaders. In 1984, Justice Minister <PERSON> Rodrigo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lara </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonilla </PERSON> was killed, and in January Attorney General <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Mauro </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyos </PERSON> was gunned down. Officials suspect drug traffickers in the deaths because both men fought narcotics.
