<HEAD>Millions of Peasants Leave Farm to Make Money, Clog Rail System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Millions of Chinese peasants have hit the road in recent weeks to seek their fortunes, creating a transportation crisis along the country's railways, an official report said. Armed police have been called out to maintain order at railway stations heaving under the mass of travelers while some passenger trains are carrying more than twice their capacity, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s domestic <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said in an article appearing in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> on Monday `` Some are going to the northwest for construction, some are going to the northeast's Daxinganling forest for lumbering, others are going <LOCATION> Gaungdong </LOCATION> province -LRB- in the south -RRB- to farm and still others are going to large cities as housekeepers,'' the news service said. At the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> station, the report said, `` people can be found everywhere sleeping in the open.'' In <LOCATION> Zhengzhou </LOCATION>, the capital of central <LOCATION> Henan </LOCATION> province and a railroad hub, more than 10,000 people were said to be waiting at the station for tickets. The news service recounted the woeful tale of one passenger who stood for more than 30 hours on a train trip from <LOCATION> Anhui </LOCATION> province to the far-north city of <LOCATION> Harbin </LOCATION>. At one point he lifted his swollen foot only to find the tiny space immediately seized by a traveler squeezed next to him. Nearly 4 million people ride the rails daily, the report said, without saying how much of an increase that represents. Most of the travelers are peasants looking for work, the report said. The exodus from rural homes began with the arrival of warmer weather following last month's Lunar New Year holiday. Poor peasants always have sought their fortune in big cities, but the situation has become a problem in recent years because of recent economic reforms that ease travel restrictions and permit labor markets. The railroad situation hits its most critical on the third, sixth and ninth days of each month, which are considered propitious days for travel, the news agency said. Although authorities are taking several steps to ease the situation, such as increasing passenger trains, the transportation crisis is expected to continue, the report said. In an earlier report, <ORGANIZATION> Sichuan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> said March 2 that 100,000 travelers were trying to leave <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION>, the capital of central <LOCATION> Sichuan </LOCATION> province, every day for their hometowns, by rail. `` A few passengers, heedless of admonitions, have stormed their way onto the trains by breaking the windows,'' the report said. `` At the same time, trains leaving <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION> station for destinations outside <LOCATION> Sichuan </LOCATION> are seriously overloaded to the extend that it is impossible to open the doors or supply drinking water.''
