<HEAD>Polar Bear Killed After Man Enters Cage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A zoo polar bear injured a man with a history of mental problems who entered its cage, and police shot the bear to death, authorities say. The 28-year-old man, whose identity was not released, was treated at a hospital for a gash on his head and was put under emergency detention by police after the Sunday morning incident. Police said it was unclear why the man climbed into the bear's cage, but that the man told doctors he did it to `` give his brother strength,'' and that people `` need a show of courage. The `` brother'' reference was unexplained. Vilas Zoo director <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said the intruder had to scale a wall or climb through a moat to reach the the 7-foot-4, 900-pound bear, named Chief. `` I'd say it's a one in a million chance that you get out of a polar bear's den alive when a polar bear is in it,'' <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said. A jogger who heard shouts flagged down a motorist, who alerted police. The jogger, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, 47, said the `` bear was standing above the person, licking him, playing around with him. The man was n't screaming. He was n't doing anything. I thought he was dead.'' Police Officer <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Puls </PERSON> fatally wounded the bear with a 12-gauge shotgun after yelling at it and firing shots in the air in an attempt to scare it. <PERSON> Puls </PERSON> said he shot the animal after it began to drag the man to its cave. <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said Chief, the only polar bear at the municipal zoo, was considered one of the largest in captivity. It had been with the zoo for about 13 -LCB- years. `` He was a good show and everyone liked him,'' <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said. `` But you ca n't compare his to a human life. All of us in the zoo profession know that a human life takes precedent.'' Police said the Sunday incident was the third time this year that emergency detention procedures had to be used to detain the man. Those procedures