<HEAD>Judge Rules Bayh Eligible To Be Indiana Governor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHELBYVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Shelby </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> judge today ruled that Secretary of State <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON> meets the constitutional five-year residency requirement to be governor. In a 10-page ruling, <ORGANIZATION> Shelby </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judge </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> concluded the Democratic gubernatorial candidate did n't lose his <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> residency when he worked as an attorney in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, in 1983 and 1984. Republicans had argued that <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON>, who leads public opinion polls in the governor's race, lost his <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> residency when he moved to the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> to work for the law firm of <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hartson </PERSON>. But <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> concluded that <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON> always intended to return to his home state and never established formal residence elsewhere. `` Personal presence -LRB- away -RRB- from one's place of domicile is insufficient to change one's domicile,'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> wrote. `` One must move to another place with the intent to make it his home and without the intention of returning to his home as such.'' The judge's decision came after a one-day trial Friday on <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON>'s lawsuit seeking a declaratory judgment that he meets the constitutional requirement to be governor <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON> filed the suit in February after Republican Gov. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Orr </PERSON> instructed the <ORGANIZATION> GOP-controlled </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> to investigate <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON>'s eligibility. The election board last week delayed its probe to allow the court to rule. The election board and <PERSON> Orr </PERSON> already have called for any lower court decision to be appealed to the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> concluded that <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON> repeatedly expressed his intent to return to his home state and considered his stint in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> as only a brief episode of professional development. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> noted that <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON>, the son of former Sen. <PERSON> Birch </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON>, voted regularly in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> and kept his ties to the state Democratic organization. <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON>, 32, faces opposition from former <LOCATION> Kokomo </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. Daily in the May 3 Democratic primary. Lt. Gov. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mutz </PERSON> is unopposed for the Republican nomination to succeed <PERSON> Orr </PERSON>, who is barred by the Constitution from seeking a third straight term.
