<HEAD>Iran Forced To Import More Oil Products After Air Raids, Survey
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has been forced to sharply increase imports of refined petroleum products because <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> air raids have badly damaged some of its refineries, the <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Survey </ORGANIZATION> reported today. The attacks also have forced <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to ration gasoline for the first time. The weekly oil industry newsletter said <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s Laripax company chartered the 284,298-ton Liberian supertanker Patria to carry 1.8 million barrels of gas oil to the Iranian port of <PERSON> Bandar </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Rotterdam </LOCATION>. It said two shipments totalling 900,000 barrels of gas oil were delivered to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> earlier this month. Gas oil, a refined fuel heavier than kerosene, is often used as a diesel fuel. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, a major oil producer, has been importing around 300,000 barrels a day of refined products for 18 months because <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> air strikes have reduced its refining capacity. The newsletter said that a big refinery on <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s southern outskirts was badly damaged in an Iraqi air raid Feb. 27 and its output of 220,000 barrels a day curtailed. That attack triggered a renewed `` war of the cities'' between the two countries, at war for 7 -LCB- years, with both sides lobbing long-range missiles into each other capitals. The survey said another refinery in the northwestern city of <LOCATION> Tabriz </LOCATION> was only working at around half its normal capacity of 80,000 barrels a day. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s refining capacity of around 1.3 million barrels a day is believed to have been slashed by as much as 66 percent since the war began. The Iraqi air force has been concentrating on hitting Iranian oil industry targets, the mainstay of its economy, since 1984. The newsletter estimated that despite these attacks, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> is producing around 1.9 million barrels a day and exporting around 1.5 million barrels a day through the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. Industry sources said the Iranians are driving to expand their refining capacity. The <LOCATION> Isfahan </LOCATION> plant has been upgraded to a capacity of 280,000 barrels a day. The Iranians also are moving ahead with plans to build new plants at <LOCATION> Arak </LOCATION> in western <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Bandar </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> on the gulf coast. They would have a combined capacity of more than 250,000 barrels a day that would restore <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s refining self-sufficiency. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s domestic consumption is estimated at around 700,000 barrels a day.
