<HEAD>Lab Halts Shipment of Polio Vaccine for AIDS Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The only <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturer of injectable polio vaccine has stopped shipping the drug to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> physicians after learning it was being used as an experimental AIDS treatment. Connaught Laboratories' Vice President <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said the company would like to cooperate in such a treatment but is prohibited by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> from supplying physicians with the vaccine for anything other than its intended use _ to prevent polio. `` Some doctors in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> have been working with AIDS patients, using our injectable polio product,'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. `` As soon as it came to our attention, we were required to contact the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> to determine if they had all the approvals.'' He said the physicians did not have the required approvals, so Connaught halted the shipments. A spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said an `` investigational new drug application'' should be submitted to the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> and studied to be sure experiments are conducted properly and that dosages would not adversely affect patients. `` The risks have to be weighed versus the benefits,'' she said. The old injectable <PERSON> Salk </PERSON> vaccine is no longer the preferred polio vaccine in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, having been replaced by an oral vaccine. It has shown promise for AIDS patients, relieving some cancer lesions, herpes infections, swollen lymph nodes and fatigue, a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> researcher reported. The old, killed-virus vaccine can only be supplied by <PERSON> Connaught </PERSON>. Dr. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> researcher and co-developer of the experimental treatment, said physicians wonder what will happen now to patients who have shown improvement after receiving the injections for as long as two years. `` Patients with cancers are getting better and doctors can no longer give them treatment. Most are close to running out,'' he said Friday, adding that the physicians planned to meet to form a plan of action. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said studies on more than 50 patients have shown the vaccine `` produces clinical benefits after six weeks.'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said that it's up to Connaught, not the doctors, to submit the necessary applications to the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>, and alleged that the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> lab has financial reasons for not releasing its vaccine. `` What they want to provide is a new vaccine which they have a patent for, opposed to the old Salk vaccine which is in the publc domain,'' he said. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said the company did receive a patent in November for an improved injectable polio vaccine for global use, but he insisted Connaught is not pushing one over the other for experiments on AIDS patients. `` We started working on the new vaccine in 1979-80, probably before AIDS was a household word, `` he said.
