<HEAD>Gore Says He's Alternative Illinois Wants</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 5 grafs with Gore comment today, picking up in
5th graf pvs, Gore's campaign</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> portrayed himself today as a needed alternative to the three Democratic candidates leading him in polls one day before the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> primary. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> greeted workers during a shift change at a factory in <LOCATION> Rockford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, and said, `` I'm very encouraged'' about Tuesday's primary, although he and his aides acknowledged on Sunday that he was far behind `` I think there are an awful lot of voters here in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> who want an alternative to the kind of approach offered by <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. I offer a different kind of approach,'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said today. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> on Sunday had turned his focus to Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and said the vice president's response to the Iran-Contra affair amounted to: `` Gee whiz, that's great, let's go ahead.'' The Tennesseean resumed his <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> campaign after a weekend break, returning to a state where polls show him stuck in single digits far behind favorite sons <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, and also trailing rival <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s campaign bought what deputy campaign manager <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON> called `` a decent or modest amount'' of television airtime in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. It was thought to be in the range of $ 200,000 to $ 300,000 over the past week. But <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON> downplayed expectations, saying <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s only aim was to be `` in the fray'' in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. `` We never put any serious organizational effort into <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON> said. He cited <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s and <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>'s strength and the timing a week after last week's Super Tuesday round of primaries that catapulted <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> to the top tier of Democratic presidential contenders <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> delivered a forceful attack on the vice president and the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for the Iran-Contra affair in a long question-and-answer session with students at <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> law school. He pointed to the guilty plea by former White House National Security Adviser <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> McFarlane </PERSON> to misdemeanor charges relating to Iran-Contra as confirming `` the Reagan-Bush administration violated the law in a brazen way.'' `` We still do n't know what <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s role was,'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said the administration's sale of arms to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in a bid to free hostages would have been `` hooted'' down as `` nuts'' if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was consulted. `` We did n't have that opportunity, but <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had that opportunity,'' he said. `` He evidently said, ` yeah, gee whiz, that's great, let's go ahead,''' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> voiced sympathy for <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> senator whose <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bid is on the ropes in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, for a television ad being aired by <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. It says a vote for <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> is in effect a vote for a confused race and perhaps a brokered convention. `` Gov. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>'s commercial tries to lump him in with back-room politics of a kind <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> has not been associated with,'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said at a news conference. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> continued to depict himself as a more electable alternative to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and his other rivals but did not dwell on them in a series of speeches in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> area. But asked about <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> by the law students, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said he would respond `` with relish.'' He repeated his contention that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> lacks necessary foreign policy experience and said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has wrongly stated that there is no `` underclass'' in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> _ the <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> senator asserting that children trapped in a cycle of poverty do make up such an underclass. And he faulted <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for shortcomings as a campaigner. `` I think he's not yet found his voice to articulate his message beyond the ` <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Miracle,''' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said, referring to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' claim that he helped turn around his state's economy. `` I do n't think he has succeeded in offering a clear vision of what he would do as president,'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said his decision to spend Friday night through Sunday morning in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> did not reflect an abandonment of his hopes for <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. He said he spent much of the time raising money by telephone, and said his fund-raisers have collected as much as $ 150,000 a day since last Tuesday. But acknowledging the polls in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said: `` There are two favorite sons here; I understand that.''
