<HEAD>Nurses Across Britain Protest To Demand More NHS Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of nurses at hospitals across <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> held strikes, rallies and marches today in a last-minute attempt to get the Conservative government to allocate more money to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Bus services were halted or slowed on dozens of routes as crews at some some <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> transport centers walked out in sympathy, said <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, where about 500 nurses mounted picket lines at 15 hospitals, nurses delivered a cake with a message to Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, who will unveil the budget in Parliament on Tuesday. `` We hope we will get a bigger slice of the budget,'' said 19-year-old student nurse <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Hogg </PERSON>. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s government, expected to make substantial tax cuts, has ruled out a big increase in the service's $ 41 billion budget Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> has ordered a review of the service and plans to encourage more Britons to take out private health insurance. Outside the capital, strikes were `` fairly limited,'' according to the <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION>, one of two health unions sponsoring the protest. The third major union, the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nurses </ORGANIZATION>, has a no-strike code of principle. Overall, 515,000 nurses work in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> province, 10,000 nurses took part in protest marches. In <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION>, nurses presented a 60,000-signature petition to the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Outside <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, strikes were reported at two hospitals in <LOCATION> Manchester </LOCATION> and one in <LOCATION> Cheshire </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> Yorkshire </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Wakefield </PERSON>, and at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> and other hospitals in <LOCATION> Leeds </LOCATION>. Pickets or marches were held in <LOCATION> Brighton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nottingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Leicester </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Coventry </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, and Coventry.
