as the tip of the iceberg,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Ciresi </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> attorney who represents <PERSON> Esther </PERSON> <PERSON> Kociemba </PERSON>, a Melrose woman who claims to have been made infertile by the Copper-7. `` Once all the documents are disclosed -LRB- to the public -RRB-, they will collectively establish without a doubt that the Copper-7 causes -LRB- infection -RRB- and <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> knew about it, but did not disclose it to doctors or to women,'' <PERSON> Coresi </PERSON> said. Nationally, there have been 17 trials over <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>'s Copper-7, 14 of them decided in the company's favor. <PERSON> Kociemba </PERSON>'s case `` will be the first case tried against <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> where the jury will be presented with evidence from <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>'s files showing what <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> knew about the hazards of the IUD, when they knew about them and what they did about them _ which was to conceal the information,'' <PERSON> Ciresi </PERSON> said. Strain said, `` We are confident when a jury hears all the evidence, reviews all the documents and, most importantly, hears from the doctors that they will conclude the Copper-7 is a good IUD that does not cause infection.'' A major issue will be whether Copper-7's withdrawal `` tail'' string was a single strand of polypropylene incapable of transporting infection-causing bacteria into the uterus, as <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> contends, or if it was made up of many tiny strands that could act as a tunnel for bacteria, as <PERSON> Ciresi </PERSON> contends. One of the Searle documents quotes a company official saying for the first time that, although the Copper-7 string is considered a single line, it actually is a `` bundle of fused micro-filaments.''
