<FIRST>r i AM-Zimbabwe-Rain     03-14 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zimbabwe-Rain,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop-Killing Rains Follow Devastating Drought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN EDLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farmers who prayed for rain during a devastating three-year drought have faced nearly four months of almost daily downpours, which threaten to wash away any chance of an agricultural rebound. The rains that began in November have caused widespread flooding in rural areas, swelling rivers, turning streets into streams, and virtually isolating some villages by knocking out phone lines and bridges. It also has severely hampered the recovery of farmers who five months ago were in the throes of drought, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minstry </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. Last week, eight soldiers drowned while fording a flood-swollen river in the eastern highlands. By the weekend, police said 66 people had been killed by lightning since the first storms broke. `` We're working all hours and weekends too,'' said <PERSON> Temba </PERSON> <PERSON> Munyarara </PERSON>, a handyman who works mainly in poor black suburbs. `` It's sad to see the damage that's being done but it's been good for me.'' It is in the countryside, where most of <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>'s 8.2 million people live, that floods threaten agricultural recovery after the long drought. About 70 percent of the population depends on agriculture for income. Likewise, the bulk of the land-locked nation's export income comes from cash crops such as cotton, coffee, corn, sugar, tea and tobacco. Last year, agricultural output fell 18 percent, or $ 180 million, as a result of drought. Business Trends, the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chartered </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>'s monthly economic analysis, reported that the losses would be recouped with the onset of the regular rains. But the agriculture ministry's most recent crop and livestock report says that in most areas, further widespread rain will `` do more harm than good.'' Cotton, peanuts and tobacco are being severely damaged, the report said, but it predicted that if the rains ease off, <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> still can expect bumper harvests. The report also said ample water has been stored underground and in lakes and dams to carry <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> through the coming dry season, which usually lasts from May to October.
