<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Placido </PERSON> <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Agnes </PERSON> <PERSON> Baltsa </PERSON> are two opera stars who know how to put passion and drama into their singing even when they're not performing in a staged production. The tenor and the mezzo-soprano demonstrated their talents in a gala concert Sunday night at the Metropolitan Opera. The benefit for the Met pension fund was sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opera </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> and followed by a champagne supper, underwritten by <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. Since most operatic love duets are written for tenors and sopranos, <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> and Miss <PERSON> Baltsa </PERSON> sang three duets of a more confrontational nature. Their voices blended beautifully but made the sparks fly. They sang a dramatic scene from <PERSON> Verdi </PERSON>'s `` Aida,'' in which <PERSON> Amneris </PERSON> makes one last offer to Radames _ take me and save your life. Even on that basis, he turns her down. They sang <PERSON> Santuzza </PERSON> angrily accusing Turiddu of being unfaithful in <LOCATION> Mascagni </LOCATION>'s `` Cavalleria Rusticana'' and Turiddu being angry back, lying and denying it. And, building to the most familiar but still the most spine-tingling, they sang <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> pleading with <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON> to take him back in Act 4 of <PERSON> Bizet </PERSON>'s `` Carmen.'' When she turns him down, he stabs her to death. In that number, the chorus, facing the audience, was too loud. In staged performances, the chorus is behind the `` bullring'' at the back of the stage. <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> has a glorious voice for everything he sang. In a `` <PERSON> Luisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>'' aria, for instance, he was vocally always masculine and strong but could at the same time sound soft and tender in the quiet lines. He was completely equal to the Verdi music but never overpowered it. Miss <PERSON> Baltsa </PERSON>'s voice sounds dark in its low tones and light, almost white, in its top. There is n't a break in her register; her voice seems to shade gradually. In her first aria, from <PERSON> Rossini </PERSON>'s `` The Lady of the <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>,'' it was a bit disconcerting Then one became used to it. She used that shading and other vocal colors to strong dramatic effect, especially as <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON>. She sang the title role in `` Carmen'' at the Met last season. This season the concert is her only appearance. <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON>, who made his Met debut in `` Cavalleria Rusticana,'' is singing in `` The Tales of <PERSON> Hoffmann </PERSON>'' and `` Otello'' at the Met this season. <PERSON> Nello </PERSON> <PERSON> Santi </PERSON> conducted. The orchestra played overtures by <PERSON> Rossini </PERSON> and <PERSON> Verdi </PERSON> and a <LOCATION> Mascagni </LOCATION> intermezzo and sounded clear and fresh. The chorus, with the women in gowns of their choice, also sounded splendid in <PERSON> Verdi </PERSON>'s `` Anvil Chorus'' from `` Il Trovatore'' and `` Va, pensiero'' from `` Nabucco.''
