<HEAD>Archaeologists Find Site of Ancient Mediterranean Wreck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An archaeological team has found pottery from a vessel that sank about 2,400 years ago in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, a spokesman for the group said Monday. Divers found the wreck site buried in mud and silt in the crater of a submerged volcano near the island of <LOCATION> Isola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Panarea </LOCATION> off northern <LOCATION> Sicily </LOCATION>, said the spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archaeological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> for <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. One diver wrote in the team's log that the wreck looks `` as if the gods had been sitting down to a banquet, and then, for some reason, they had to dash off, overturning the tables in their haste and knocking down all the crockery,'' the spokesman said. The cups, plates, jugs, bowls and lamps are made of red clay and painted with a high-quality, black glaze, said the spokeman, who asked not to be identified. `` All that is visible on the seabed is a spread of pottery,'' he said. `` It is too early to judge with any confidence how much of the wreck survives.
