<SECOND>AM-Tax Penalties,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRS Endorses Review of Tax Penalties Which Critics Say Hurt Poor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> pledged support Monday to a review of tax penalties that were assessed last year in some 27 million cases _ penalties that have been criticized as a special burden on the poor. At the opening of a public inquiry into the maze of 154 penalties the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> can impose, <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> expressed the agency's own concern about the penalties, many of which were enacted by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> over the past seven years in an effort to increase compliance with the tax laws. `` A penalty system that operates based on the wrong principles may provide appropriate sanctions for some types of behavior and yet have an overall negative impact on taxpayer behavior because it is not perceived as fair,'' <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> said. Several witnesses at Monday's hearing accused the government of using penalties to raise revenues, rather than to assure compliance with the laws. Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>, D-Ark., chairman of a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee that oversees the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>, cited the case of one business that underpaid employment taxes by 2 cents and was hit with a penalty of $ 400.29 `` We've created some sort of a monster here,'' <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> said. `` We're going to change that some way.'' <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> and <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Donaldson </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapoton </PERSON>, assistant secretary of the treasury for tax policy, endorsed a thorough review of tax penalties. A review also was endorsed by the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> and associations representing lawyers, accountants and other tax professionals. `` We certainly hope there's not any reaction ... by <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> agents in the field ... that penalties should be used as means of raising revenue,'' <PERSON> Chapoton </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Akron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taxation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> said that when one penalty is stacked atop another, it indicates a goal of raising revenue. A major problem with penalties, said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Childs </PERSON>, director of the university's tax clinic program, is that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has not given the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> sufficient guidance on how penalties should be applied. As a result, he said, penalties often are applied to taxpayers who have neither the funds to hire a lawyer or accountant nor knowledge of how the system works. `` The low-income taxpayer has about as much knowledge of how to obtain abatement of a penalty through problems resolution -LRB- the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>' `` consumer advocate'' -RRB- as he-she does of getting to the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Childs </PERSON> `` Abuses by high-income taxpayers have brought about a plethora of new penalties. Unfortunately, the low-income taxpayer has been caught in this net.'' An even more basic problem, <PERSON> Childs </PERSON> said, is the difficulty in reading <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> tax forms in general. He cited a finding that instructions for Form 1040EZ _ the simplest tax form _ require an 8.45 grade reading level, compared to a 7.1 level to read the Wall Street Journal. Penalties in the tax law range from $ 1 for failing to file a statement on payment of dividends totaling less than $ 10 to a maximum of 25 percent of the tax owed for failing to pay on time to $ 10,000 for abetting a corporation in the understatement of its tax liability. In 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> assessed 27 million penalties totaling $ 14 billion and excused another 4 million for $ 4 billion. <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> criticized <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> for the way it applies penalties against taxpayers who file what the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> considers frivolous returns. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> created the penalty, which can be as much as $ 500, to discourage taxpayers from using arguments such as self-incrimination to avoid a proper tax return. <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> said he has evidence the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> is imposing the penalty against those who write critical notes to the agency on their returns, even though the returns are completed and signed. He cited the much-publicized case of a <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> woman who was hit with a penalty for such behavior and whose husband's life insurance policy was seized before a federal judge intervened. `` If that little old lady lived in <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, would she get the same penalty?'' <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON>. `` Who makes those decisions?'' <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> promised to check into the <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> case but <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> quickly cautioned against it. `` I do n't think she wants you to review her case and flag her return,'' the senator said.
</TEXT>
