<HEAD>Rights Group Rips Philippines Military For Civilian Atrocities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES W. HATTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The military is killing and terrorizing civilians under the pretense of fighting communism, and the campaign has gone unchecked by the government, a human rights group charged Monday. Task Force-Detainees, a group formed by the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> to monitor rights violations under ousted President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, charged that the military began its spree two months ago in northeastern <LOCATION> Aurora </LOCATION> province. It called for an investigation and claimed that atrocities included the Feb. 11 slaying of <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivares </PERSON>, a leftist provincial leader who helped organize the group's probe. At a news conference, the group introduced a 6-year-old boy who said he was the only member of his family to survive a Jan. 23 massacre. Five others died. `` I saw soldiers shoot my father and mother, after which they turned to me and shot me in both legs,'' said <PERSON> Ronaldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Guzman </PERSON>, his legs in casts. The rights group also claimed more than 1,000 people had fled their homes in the town of <LOCATION> Dinalungan </LOCATION>, about 120 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, to escape military operations. It said the violence was being waged under the guise of battling the 19-year-old communist insurgency in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. `` In the past, during <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' time, we had military in the towns in the north but there was not this kind of strafing, massacre and burning of houses,'' said Bishop <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Xavier </PERSON> <PERSON> Labayen </PERSON>. `` We're sitting on a powder keg. In a statement, the group said: `` Task Force-Detainees hopes that President -LRB- <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> will not simply dismiss this violation as yet another ` total lie' but instead will treat the matter with grave concern.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> became president in 1986 after <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> was toppled from power. <PERSON> Bienvenido </PERSON> <PERSON> Amora </PERSON>, chief investigator for the government's <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, said he would contact the group about the charges. `` We would have appreciated it very much if the Task Force-Detainees had brought this matter to the attention of the <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> so that the -LRB- commission -RRB- could proceed to investigate this case accordingly,'' he said. Last week, the <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said its investigation showed 7,444 Filipino civilians were arrested illegally last year, eclipsing the 5,967 arrests in 1985 under <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. Spokesman <PERSON> Noel </PERSON> <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON> said 672 of those detained in 1987 were tortured. The same day, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> claimed similar atrocities in a report released in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> branded the Amnesty report `` one-sided'' and charged it had relied on Task Force-Detainees for its information. She challenged both groups to provide evidence.
