<FIRST>r i AM-HungerStriker     03-14 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hunger Striker,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greek Hunger Striker Demands Right Not to Join Army</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELENA SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AVLON, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 31-year-old pacifist on Monday entered the fourth week of a hunger strike to try to win an alternative to compulsory military service. In October, a military court sentenced <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Marangakis </PERSON> to four years in prison on insubordination charges. On Feb. 22, an appeals court reduced his sentence to 26 months. The 6-foot 5-inch woodcarver, who weighed 222 pounds, started his hunger strike the next day. He said he has lost 22 pounds since then and will take only fruit juice and milk every other day until the Greek government establishes conscientious objection to military service. `` I wo n't eat until the government recognizes the right of the individual to act on the basis of conscience,'' <PERSON> Marangakis </PERSON> said in an interview at <LOCATION> Avlon </LOCATION> military prison 29 miles north of <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>. Military service is compulsory in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, where it averages about 21 months. Unlike some other European countries, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> offers no option to compulsory service, and objectors are routinely given long prison terms. Legal experts say there are about 300 Greeks imprisoned for refusing to serve in the military. Almost all are <PERSON> Jehovah </PERSON>'s Witnesses <PERSON> Marangakis </PERSON> belongs to one of the ancient Eastern Orthodox churches but says his pacifism is derived mainly from personal ideals rather than his religion. <PERSON> Stelios </PERSON> <PERSON> Nestos </PERSON>, one of <PERSON> Marangakis </PERSON>' three attorneys, said that 11 other conscientious objectors had recently gone into hiding after they were called up. But <PERSON> Marangakis </PERSON> presented himself to a military camp in Drama, in northern <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, where he was called up in March 1987. <PERSON> Marangakis </PERSON> said he was planning to appeal his sentence to <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. A new law under debate in the Greek parliament seeks to abolish prison terms for conscientious objectors but does n't provide for alternative service. Instead, conscientious objectors will be required to serve double time in the armed forces as non-combatants. But <PERSON> Marangakis </PERSON> said he would refuse to serve as a non-combatant because it represents a form of military service.
</TEXT>
