<HEAD>Botha Says Main Issue in Angola is Timetable for Cuban Withdrawal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA WATSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s foreign minister said Monday that <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> has not presentated a plan for withdrawal of the estimated 40,000 Cuban troops in that country and a timetable remains a central issue for regional peace. <PERSON> Roelof </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> was asked at a news conference about an announcement Sunday by <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> that it and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> had given <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials proposals for a southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> peace accord including a timetable for <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> troop withdrawal. He replied: `` That is not correct.'' In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said Monday the <LOCATION> Angolan </LOCATION> proposal `` appears to break no new ground'' on the issue of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s military presence in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said the withdrawal timetable, along with who would supervise the pullout, `` is the issue that must be taken up.'' He spoke to reporters after a day of talks with <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistant secretary of state who specializes in southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, aimed at advancing plans for peace in the region. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said they had `` extensive'' discussions of the situation in southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and `` the question of <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> withdrawal as a prerequisite for implementing a settlement in <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa-Namibia </LOCATION>. We discussed extensively the possibilities that exist in this respect.'' `` I've received interesting information,'' he added, and described the talks as `` useful'' but would not give details. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said he and <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON> might meet again Tuesday, but that nothing was set. Since 1981, <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON> has tried to negotiate a withdrawal of Cuban troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> in return for an end to South African control over neighboring <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, also known as <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. His last meeting with <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> was two years ago. Cuban troops help <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s Marxist government fight the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> for the Total Independence of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>, a guerrilla force backed by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In January, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> declared a willingness in principle to leave <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> but no deal has been negotiated. On Sunday, <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Jonas </PERSON> <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> had told him it would begin direct talks with <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> on the Angolan civil war, which began with independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> in 1975. Asked about this at the news conference, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> responded: `` I have said that I have no problem in talking directly with <LOCATION> Luanda </LOCATION> -LRB- the Angolan capital -RRB- and to a large number of other African states.'' He denied reports that preliminary talks for such negotiations had been held. `` It's not necessary,'' he said. `` I could pick up a telephone and talk now.'' <PERSON> Kundi </PERSON> <PERSON> Payama </PERSON>, No. 2 man in <LOCATION> Luanda </LOCATION>, repeated that <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> was prepared to negotiate direc