<HEAD>Sikh Militants Kill 15 In Punjab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sikh extremists killed 21 people in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state, including a family of four, it was reported Monday. Police shot and killed <PERSON> Balraj </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, a Sikh radical wanted for several murders in <LOCATION> Patiala </LOCATION> on Monday, according to the state police control center in <LOCATION> Chandigarh </LOCATION>. The deaths late Sunday and early Monday raised to at least 451 the number of killings blamed on <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> radicals this year. Sikh militants have been fighting since 1982 for more autonomy or an independent homeland for the sect in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. The northern state, the country's richest agricultural area, is the only one of Hindu-dominated <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> where Sikhs have a majority. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported that <PERSON> Sardul </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, his wife and two daughters were shot to death early Monday in <LOCATION> Jhander </LOCATION>, a village in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION>. The gunmen burned the family's house to the ground before fleeing, it said. Responsibility was claimed by the <ORGANIZATION> Bhindranwale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tiger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, one of more than a dozen radical groups in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. Police said a note left at the scene said <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, a Sikh, was being `` punished'' for extortion and looting, but they gave no details. Eight other people were slain in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION>, including four Hindus in <LOCATION> Dallin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> village </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> UNI </ORGANIZATION> said. A retired Sikh police constable identified as <PERSON> Gajjan </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> was shot to death in <LOCATION> Ludhiana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> and two Hindu men were pulled from a truck and shot down in <LOCATION> Jalandhar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION>, the news agency reported. Both districts are in central <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. A group of Sikh militants riding a jeep sprayed bullets at a bus terminus in <LOCATION> Hoshiarpur </LOCATION> killing six people on the spot, police in <LOCATION> Chandigarh </LOCATION> said. The identitities of the victims were not immediately known. Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s government has been trying to stem the violence since last May, when it removed the state administration and put <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> under federal rule. On March 4, <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> ordered five Sikh high priests released from jail in an apparent effort to get them involved against terrorism. He dissolved the <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Assembly </LOCATION> two days later, paving the way for militants to compete in anticipated elections. There have been no signs, however, that priests and other Sikh leaders will move against the radicals.
