<HEAD>25,500 Held On Eve of Strike In India</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 25,000 people were taken into police custody Monday as authorities moved to block a nationwide strike to protest corruption and official incompetence, officials said. Nine opposition parties, including the communists, have scheduled the strike for Tuesday to protest government corruption, failure to halt secterian violence and to demand better facilities for farmers and farm laborers. Police in the southern state of <LOCATION> Madras </LOCATION> took 25,000 people into custody to halt violence during the strike, a police officer in state capital of <LOCATION> Madras </LOCATION> said. UNI reported that 500 people were arrested in the eastern <LOCATION> Orissa </LOCATION> state. It said state governments across <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> deployed additional security forces Monday to guard important installations and to maintain law and order. Besides the two communist parties, the major sponsor of the strike is the `` Jan Morcha'' or <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, an umbrella group of disgruntled members of Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s govering <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> party. The parties have accused the government of failure to contain Sikh separatist violence in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> where 450 people were killed by suspected Sikh radicals this year. Radical Sikhs want to seceede from the Indian union and turn the state of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> into an independent Sikh nation. Opposition leaders have also accused <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> of shielding members of his party from corruption inquiries involving foreign arms deals.
