<FIRST>r i AM-AthensTraffic     03-14 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Athens Traffic,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cars, Taxis Banned in Anti-Pollution Drive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government banned more than 800,000 cars and taxis from the downtown commercial district Monday to combat the city's acrid, eye-stinging smog. Hundreds of policemen were stationed along three central arteries that form a triangle around the city's main shopping zone, blocking 45 streets. The ban is part of a campaign started in January to disperse a thick brown cloud known as the `` Nefos'' that hangs over the city. Scientists have blamed it on emissions from cars, diesel-powered taxis and aging buses. The cloud forms over the mountain-ringed <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> basin when there are sudden changes in temperature, and pollutants are trapped in a still layer of air near the ground. Under the new rules, trucks will be allowed in the downtown commercial district for four hours in the morning and 2 -LCB- hours in the afternoon to resupply shops. The area's 100 permanent residents were issued special permits for their vehicles. Police Lt. <PERSON> Panayiotis </PERSON> <PERSON> Stathatos </PERSON>, in charge of applying the measures, said there was a total traffic ban on 14 streets and a partial ban on 31 streets from 7 a.m. to 8 p.m. `` So far, we've had about a 60 percent success rate. A lot of drivers still do n't know what streets have been blocked to traffic, so we are showing a little lenience to violators,'' he said. Drivers face an $ 85 fine for illegally entering the one square-mile district near Constitution Square. Another measure already in force bans half the city's private cars and half its 15,000 taxis from entering the 5-square-mile inner city area on alternate days. Vehicles circulate there according to the last digit on their license plates. As part of the pollution-cutting campaign, the government has also abolished the traditional afternoon siesta in favor of a continuous workday for stores and ordered strict checks on industrial emissions. At least one group opposed Monday's ban. `` It's created a mess. It was taken quickly, spasmodically and without sound planning,'' said <PERSON> Panaghis </PERSON> <PERSON> Stavrides </PERSON>, vice-president of the 1,600-member <ORGANIZATION> Athens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The latest traffic restrictions will last through May, when their effects will be evaluated.
</TEXT>
