<SECOND>AM-Recycling Scavengers,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trash Scavengers Competing With Recycling Program For Trash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scavengers are competing with a pilot recycling program by picking up newspapers and cans put out by residents for special collection, officials say. `` It's easy pickings for these scavengers to come along and supplement their income,'' says <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>, a recycling consultant who designed the new program in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> neighborhood. `` We've got so many people putting -LRB- recyclable -RRB- material out that it's easy to pick up a ton of newspaper in an hour,'' he said. He estimated the program was losing about $ 200 every seven days because the scavengers were helping themselves to about four tons of newspaper weekly. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said the neighborhood program's revenues vary from week-to-week depending on the number of tons collected, hitting a peak of about $ 1,400 per week. So, he estimated that the loss would represent from 15 percent to 20 percent of weekly revenues. `` We've got two different recycling systems converging and it's not bad from a recycling point of view,'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said `` But it cuts into the money for the program.'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>, who also is a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recycling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, an organization of 400 recycling businesses, said scavengers operate all ovr the country. `` They're called alley entrepreneurs,'' he said. `` Some of these people have developed shrewd operations. They're not always street people. Some of them are sophisticated business people who are making enough money for a bare living,'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> has an estimated 1,500 scavengers, he said. They make anywhere from $ 30 to $ 150 a week sifting aluminimu cans, bottles and newspaperes from the 9,000 tons of garbage produced daily in the city, he said. The city's 20 privately run recycling centers pay an average of 40 cents a pound for aluminum and about 2 cents a pound for newspaper or glass, he said. `` Some of -LRB- the scavengers -RRB- drive station wagons or pickup trucks on routes to bars and restaurants to collect aluminum cans and bottles,'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said. Though scavengers work throughout <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, a group of six to eight alley entrepreneurs is taking advantage of the five-week-old recycling program in <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> on the city's <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION>, he said. The Beverly program, a city pilot project and one of seven neighborhood recycling programs, has attracted the most participation from residents _ and the most attention from scavengers, <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said. The Resource Center, a private, non-profit recycling business that runs the Beverly program, says about 60 percent of the neighborhood's residents separate newspapers, aluminum cans and other recyclable material from their garbage and leave it at the curb in special blue boxes. Resource Center drivers pick up the trash daily, if they get there before the alley entrepreneurs. The scavengers usually raid between 6 a.m. and 8 a.m., said <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON>, director of the Resource Center. `` One gentleman is a minister at a small church that does n't support him well,'' <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> said `` So he's devised a system to recycle materials from his congregation and he also, in his free time, collects out on the streets this way to supplement his income.'' <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Resource </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> has hired some of the alley entrepreneurs to drive recycling trucks, but others say the do n't want such a formal job <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said he hopes the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> will adopt a proposed ordinance that would make it illegal for unauthorized persons to take waste set out for special recycling collections. The proposal calls for fining violators from $ 100 to $ 500. `` Trash scavenging is going to be a problem in areas with large low-income populations,'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said. `` They're trying to make 10 bucks to make it through to tomorrow. You ca n't fault them for that.''
