<HEAD>Anonymous Tests To Seek AIDS Antibodies in Newborns in 30 Cities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Newborn babies in 30 cities will be checked for AIDS antibodies in anonymous tests the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> hopes will provide an early and broader look at who is getting the disease. The tests, to be at selected hospitals, are part of a series of surveys designed to eventually test 1.6 million Americans a year for acquired immune deficiency syndrome. Blood samples from the newborns will be sent without names for testing, <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Gayle </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> said Monday. The study hopes to determine the extent to which AIDS has penetrated heterosexual women of child-bearing age, thought to be a low-risk group. Other programs, some of which are already under way, will test blood samples from sexually transmitted disease clinics, drug clinics, tuberculosis clinics, military recruits, job corps blood donors and others, she said. Some tests will be routine and anonymous while others will be voluntary with confidential results, she said. Early results are expected next fall, and the findings probably will determine which programs are continued, she said. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> is helping finance the programs at a cost of an estimated $ 47 million for fiscal 1988. Some doctors say it violates ethics to test samples from known people without permission and that getting permission would narrow the population being tested. `` This is the least offensive way of getting a reliable general population sample,'' Dr. <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Dondero </PERSON>, chief of surveillance and evaluation for the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s AIDS program. Others question whether it is ethical not to tell a patient something he or she should know. `` To simply have the results and not have the ability to do something with the results is n't a completely reasonable position, is it?'' asked Dr. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> <PERSON> Parks </PERSON>, a pediatrics professor at the <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>. Only about half the babies who test positively carry the virus. The others get a dose of antibody proteins from their infected mothers. A positive antibodies test on a baby proves only that the mother carries the virus. Similar tests on 30,000 newborns in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> revealed that one of every 476 women giving birth there was infected. Not all who carry the virus eventually develop AIDS. The newborns will be tested in 20 cities with a high AIDS incidence. They are <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Tests also will be done in the low-incidence cities of <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haven </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. Acquired immune deficiency syndrome attacks the body's ability to ward off disease. It is transmitted through sexual contact with an infected person, shared hypodermic needles and blood transfusions, and can be passed from mothers to their offspring. There is no known cure. Since June, 1981 there have been 55,167 cases counted in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and 30,932 patients have died.
