<HEAD>Infamous Criminal Now Preaches Word of God</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> was always successful: a violin player with the <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Symphony </LOCATION>, a tennis star in college, onetime national surfing champion. Later, he became famous as <PERSON> Murph </PERSON> the Surf: playboy, jewel thief, murderer. Now, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> calls himself a `` frontline Christian soldier,'' an ex-convict who has `` dedicated the rest of my life to the Lord.'' `` I've got what they call chain-gang religion, jailhouse religion, and it's easy for people to scoff at it,'' <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said during a recent interview at The Bridge, a prison work-release facility in <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, 50, said he has traveled more than 100,000 miles to counsel prisoners and has given his Christian testimony at hundreds of schools and churches. He was paroled in November 1986 after 19 years in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> prisons. One of the conditions of his release was that he spend his time helping others by preaching and teaching. Many are watching and judging, he knows. They remember that it was <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> who stole the <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION>, a 563-carat sapphire, in a spectacular heist from the Museum of Natural History in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in 1964, along with a 100-carat ruby and 20 other gems. They remember too that he was convicted of murder in the 1967 slayings of two women whose bludgeoned bodies were found dumped in <LOCATION> Whiskey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, a tidal waterway between <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>. Prosecutors said the two women were killed over $ 488,000 worth of negotiable securities they stole from their employer. `` There will always be critics or skeptics who do n't believe in born-again experiences,'' <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said. `` But I guarantee it happens and has happened to me.'' Those he works with believe in him and his work. `` His goal is to help prisoners come to Christ,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Crossley </PERSON>. `` He wants to help fight crime and wage war on drugs. I believe churchgoers should support <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>'s ministry. <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> Rainwater </PERSON>, head of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s Youth for Christ, echoes <PERSON> Crossley </PERSON>'s statements. `` I've heard nothing but real good reports on <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> since he has been paroled,'' <PERSON> Rainwater </PERSON> said. `` He has been a good representative of the Christian community.'' <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said he is just starting. `` I have a number of mentors who have been down the road before. Good Christians. Prison chaplains. People who care about people. `` <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> told us to represent him in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. My <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> is in the jails... The jails are the places I least want to be. But it's there I believe God wants me to be. It is where he allowed me to grow up.'' <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> married <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, who visited him in prison for 12 years, last December. She frequently travels with him on speaking engagements. He is sometimes paid by groups that ask him to speak. Other income comes from the sale of paintings he did while in prison. `` I do n't have wealth. I do n't have material things. I go from month to month, but God provides,'' he said. `` I never could have imagined the peace, quality and joy of such a life.'' To those who doubt or scoff, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said, `` If you do n't believe me, just watch me.''
