</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KILKENNY, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Residents of this village, settled 131 years ago by <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> homesteaders, celebrated St. Patrick's Day a bit early with their decidedly un-Irish tradition: toilet bowl racing. To the cheers of 100 onlookers Sunday, two-time champion <PERSON> Darrell </PERSON> <PERSON> Knish </PERSON> downed a cup of beer and jumped on a bowl perched on plywood and bicycle tires. Teammates whisked him down the block toward a second beer sitting on the snow-covered pavement, which he chugged before racing back up the hill ahead of a competitor. His trophy? A toilet seat cover with the names of the winning team members scrawled on the back. <PERSON> Kilkenny </PERSON>, population 180, swelled by several hundred Sunday as locals and visitors sprayed their hair green, painted shamrocks on buildings, and gulped homemade mulligan stew and beer. `` If you're going to pick a town to go to, this is it,'' said <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Taaffe </PERSON> of <PERSON> Richfield </PERSON>, who has come to the last four St. Patrick's Day celebrations in <LOCATION> Kilkenny </LOCATION>. `` If you do n't know anybody, you'll know them before you leave town,'' said <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Mach </PERSON>, son of the mayor. <PERSON> Dana </PERSON> <PERSON> Begley </PERSON>, 36, was quick to learn that. She passed through the town a while ago on a trip and liked it so much that she and her children moved here from southern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kilkenny </PERSON> was all-Irish at its founding in 1857, but mobility and marriage have gradually reduced the ranks. `` There are a few around here who are 100 percent Irish, but not many,'' said <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON>, 62, one of the 100 percenters. `` But even if the people are n't Irish, on St. Patrick's Day, they're all Irish.'' As put by <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Kewatt </PERSON>, tapping his foot to the beat in the <ORGANIZATION> Lions </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZAT