<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> businessman identified as the Drug Enforcement Agency's No. 1 heroin target has been arrested and charged with importing 1,000 pounds of heroin from <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> over three years, authorities said Monday. The drug ring run by <PERSON> Kon </PERSON> <PERSON> Yu-Leung </PERSON> <PERSON> Kon </PERSON> was much larger than those in such well-known heroin smuggling cases as the French Connection or the Pizza Connection, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stutman </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office. The French Connection involved 70 pounds of heroin, the Pizza Connection about 200, he said. Heroin trafficking `` is now controlled by <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> ethnic groups that are bringing in vast amounts to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, in amounts far more than any of us who have been professionals in the field ever thought possible,'' <PERSON> Stutman </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Maloney </PERSON> said federal authorities lured <PERSON> Kon </PERSON> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, where he was arrested Sunday night in front of the New York Hilton Hotel. The 44-year-old <PERSON> Kon </PERSON> was charged under an indictment handed up in December. <PERSON> Maloney </PERSON> refused to give details of the arrest. <PERSON> Stutman </PERSON> said that although <PERSON> Kon </PERSON> is charged with importing 1,000 pounds of heroin, it is believed he is responsible for bringing in twice that amount. The heroin was smuggled into the country from 1984 to 1987 through various means, including suitcases and shipments of vases, ice buckets, T-shirts and wall plaques, said <PERSON> Maloney </PERSON>. Couriers then carried millions of dollars in proceeds back to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION>