<HEAD>Senators To House: Drop Gephardt Trade Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators on Monday called on their <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> counterparts to drop Democratic presidential hopeful <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s heavily debated amendment from their sweeping trade bill. `` We decided to stick with our own Super 301 plan and to oppose the <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> amendment,'' <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said as he emerged from a meeting of <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference committee members. The move, which came on a voice vote in the closed-door meeting, could set the stage for the gradual erasure of the <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> amendment if the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> presents a compromise counteroffer to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> that makes a substantial change in the wording. However, <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said that the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s action represents `` nothing new. `` We've known the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s bargaining position for eight months,'' he said. `` It in no way reflects a decision by the conference committee. It's merely an opening bargaining position. We're confident that whatever emerges from conference will be new, forceful legislation to open foreign markets. And clearly the <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> amendment paved the way.'' <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s plan would require negotiations to reduce Japanese and other nations' `` excess and unwarranted'' trade surpluses with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. If that failed, it would prescribe presidential action to cut the surpluses by 10 percent a year. Such a move could include tariffs or import quotas on Japanese goods imported into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. But the president could refuse to act, either to uphold `` national economic security'' or if the other country were wrestling with a serious international debt problem. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has criticized the <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> plan as being likely to hurt consumers, cost more jobs than it would save and invite retaliation against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports. The administration also has been critical of the `` Super 301'' provision that the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is pushing. `` Super 301,'' named for the section of the Trade Act calling for retaliation against overseas barriers to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports, would require the president to act to eliminate all of the unfair foreign trade barriers listed on an inventory to be drawn up by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s offer was not immediately sent to the House. Instead, the senators planned to return to the bargaining table on Tuesday and fashion additional provisions involving steps to combat `` dumping,'' or selling foreign-made products in world markets at prices lower than those in home markets. They also planned to work on provisions involving countervailing duties, or tariffs that are imposed to offset the price advantage that some foreign-mad products get from export subsidies in their home countries. The senators also eased some of the provisions in the portion of their 1,000-page bill calling for retaliation against foreign unfair trade practices. They moved to expand from seven months to 12 months the time for the president to make a determination as to whether a foreign trade practice should be considered unfair. And they acted to remove some of the specific reasons for retaliation from the bill itself and put them instead in a report that will accompany the legislation.
</TEXT>
