<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said Monday that ethnic minorities stirring unrest in his vast country are raising old grievances but not challenging the authority of the Communist government. Soon after arriving on Monday in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, which has a long history of its own nationality problems, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was asked about recent demonstrations and ethnic riots in the southern Soviet republics. `` Show me the country in which there are no such problems,'' the Communist Party chief replied. `` If you show me, I will travel there right away, without stopping in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on return from <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who is on a five-day visit, is the first Soviet leader to visit <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> since the death of President <PERSON> Josip </PERSON> <PERSON> Broz </PERSON> <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> in May 1980. Referring to recent demonstrations in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, capital of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, and rioting in neighboring <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> between ethnic <PERSON> Azerbaijanis </PERSON> and Armenians that left more than 30 people dead, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said the problems had been brewing for a long time. He acknowledged some tensions between ethnic groups have been neglected in his nation of more than 100 nationalities, but said the protesters were not questioning socialist rule or `` challenging our political line.'' The remarks were his first personal comments on the situation in the Soviet south, although a statement in his name was read to <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> demonstrators. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> plans to visit <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s northernmost republic, and the Croatian city of <LOCATION> Dubrovnik </LOCATION>. Missing from his itinerary is <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, which is beset by strife between the Albanian majority and Slavic minority. Late Monday, after touring memorials and monuments, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> began talks with President <PERSON> Lazar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mojsov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bosko </PERSON> <PERSON> Krunic </PERSON>, head of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s party. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s assistant foreign minister, <PERSON> Ilija </PERSON> <PERSON> Djukic </PERSON>, briefed reporters later. He said national minorities were not raised as a separate topic, but that in a general discussion on social developments, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> stressed the difficulty of resolving ethnic problems. <PERSON> Djukic </PERSON> quoted <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> as saying, `` There are no problems that could be solved once and for all, that conditions change, that everything requires improvement.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON>, set an informal pace Monday as they took their first look at a Communist country that has implemented some of the economic reforms <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> proposes _ but with mixed results. The Soviet leader made an unscheduled stop in a busy downtown square and left his armored limousine to shake hands and chat with pedestrians. A witness said he picked up a child and gave it a kiss. Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> tried to take a walk through downtown <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> but was nearly overwhelmed by several hundred people pressing for a closer look. The Gorbachevs placed a wreath at the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier atop <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avala </LOCATION>, just outside <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>. On the way down the mountain, their limousine made an unannounced stop at a monument in the shape of a broken airplane wing that marks the site of a Soviet air disaster. On Oct. 19, 1964, a plane carrying former Soviet soldiers who helped liberate <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> 20 years earlier crashed there, killing all aboard. The <PERSON> Gorbachevs </PERSON> left two small bouquets. At one point, a reporter asked <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> if there was progress at the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> talks on the Afghan conflict. With a smile, he said `` There is,'' and `` There will be,'' but did not elaborate. He has pledged to withdraw all Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> _ estimated at 115,000 _ in less than a year if the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> talks produce a settlement. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said he came to <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> to give `` new impulses'' to the friendly relationship between the countries. Yugoslav officials have said a principal topic of discussion will be <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s economic system of `` self-managed, market socialism.'' It also allows for private initiative along lines similar to cooperative enterprises that have sprung up in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> under new laws. The Yugoslav system was developed by <PERSON> Tito </PERSON>, who broke with the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> in 1948 on ideological grounds and pursued his own communist course. While maintaining relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, he was a founder of the non-aligned movement and developed ties with the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> enjoyed a long economic boom, but has encountered hard times in recent years. Today, the government and party are struggling with annual inflation of 170 percent, 15 percent unemployment and a $ 20 billion debt to Western creditors. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is trying to end stagnation in the Soviet economy by encouraging more accountability by management and more local control of production. Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Vadim </PERSON> <PERSON> Loginov </PERSON> told reporters the Soviets are studying Yugoslav economic reforms.
