<HEAD>LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> `` Buddy'' <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, a self-styled reformer who toppled a political legend, was inaugurated governor Monday and challenged the people of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> to help him `` clean up our politics.'' The 44-year-old Democrat, who won a runoff concession from Gov. <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> on Oct. 24, took the oath of office from former Sen. <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, the son of legendary Gov. <PERSON> Huey </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, shortly after noon on the Capitol steps. He takes office amid fiscal crisis, with an accumulated budget deficit and cash shortfall of as much as $ 1.2 billion, much of it due to the oil patch depression. `` Do we have the character to clean up our politics, to free our political leadership from the stranglehold of the special interests?'' asked the former four-term congressman. `` From the governor's mansion to the <ORGANIZATION> Pardon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, from the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> to the local government, I say we do.'' `` I will lead, but I need you to pick me up when I fall,'' said <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s 51st governor. `` I need you to stand beside me when the special interests attack.'' <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, who served as governor from 1972 to 1980 and returned for a third term in 1984, was occupied for much of his last administration defending himself successfully against federal racketeering charges. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>, during an inaugural address to some 5,000 people, did not cite the usual litany of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s problems, including high unemployment, teen pregnancies, high school dropouts and nearly-empty state coffers. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> was interrupted frequently by applause, <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> included. `` I'm going hunting tomorrow,'' <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> told reporters. `` It's his now. The state's unemployment rate hit 12 percent in January, one of the highest in the nation, due primarily to the long downturn in the oil and gas industry. <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s schools are under challenge, business interests are demanding an overhaul of the tax system to attract industry and environmental groups are calling for tougher regulations to protect the air and water. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> campaigned on calls for major reforms in those areas and others, including campaign financing. He said recently that the challenge is unlike that facing any other <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> governor. `` I've got to do both to get us out of debt and build _ education development, economic development, better environment. It's going to be a difficult and interesting job,'' <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said. As solutions for the state's budget problems, <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> had proposed a statewide lottery and casino gambling in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> is opposed to both. `` We are not going to raise taxes or change taxes until we cut this budget,'' said <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>. `` It is out of control.'' Even before his inauguration, <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> won two key victories in the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> as his candidates for <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> speaker and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> president were elected during organizational meetings by lawmakers. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said earlier that a change in the legislative leadership was needed to give his ambitious programs a fair hearing by lawmakers. Before <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> was sworn in, Lt. Gov. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON>, a Republican, took the oath from former Gov. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Treen </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> defeated Lt. Gov. <PERSON> Bobby </PERSO