 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> by a vote of 7-2 refused Monday to postpone the execution of <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Felde </PERSON>, who was due to be executed in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Tuesday. Justices <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, who oppose capital punishment in all circumstances, voted to grant the stay. At the same time, the court refused <PERSON> Felde </PERSON>'s request for formal consideration of his appeal. <PERSON> Felde </PERSON>'s claimed he was denied competent representation at his 1980 trial on charges of killing a police officer because his attorney joined him in asking for the death sentence. <PERSON> Felde </PERSON> had claimed his experiences in the Vietnam War left him subject to flashbacks and unable to tell right from wrong. He described himself as a walking time bomb who would have to be executed to prevent further killings.
