<HEAD>Young Anti-Drug Lawyer Wins Bogota Mayoral Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A young lawyer who is the son of a former president and was kidnapped for campaigning against drugs has won the <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> mayor's office in the first mayoral elections in Colombian history. Security for Sunday's voting was tight throughout <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, where violence by extremist political factions and powerful narcotics traffickers is common. An alleged leader of the biggest drug organization even tried to run for city council in the town of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, but <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivas </PERSON> failed because Colombian law demands that candidates register in person. <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> is in jail in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, facing drug charges there and in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Pastrana </PERSON>, 34, son of former President <PERSON> Misael </PERSON> <PERSON> Pastrana </PERSON>, won the mayoralty election in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> and will be one of the youngest men to hold the office, which often has been a stepping stone to the presidency. <PERSON> Pastrana </PERSON> is a rising star in the <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and his election was a setback for President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON>'s governing Liberals. He was the only Conservative running for mayor in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, but feuding factions in the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> ran a total of three candidates. <PERSON> Pastrana </PERSON> got 324,801 votes and <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Caicedo </PERSON>, Liberal former president of the <ORGANIZATION> Colombian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Businessmen </ORGANIZATION>, finished second with 236,212. Voters heeded <ORGANIZATION> Barco </ORGANIZATION>'s call to fight bullets with ballots in the first election of mayors. For 169 years the president, always from either the Liberal or Conservative parties, had appointed governors who in turn chose the mayors. Colombians elected 1,008 mayors Sunday. They also chose city councils, state legislatures and governing bodies for remote territories with too few people to become states. By late Sunday night the elections office said the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> had won 405 of the races for mayor, Conservatives 379 and the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Patriotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> 13. Coalition candidates representing several parties won 104 of the mayoral contests, the elections office said. Results were not yet in from remote areas. <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> said in a speech televised Saturday night that voting would be a way to reject the violence. More than 1,700 people were killed in the past year in fighting between leftist guerrillas and government security forces and by right-wing death squads and drug traffickers. On Sunday, soldiers and police guarded voting places and patrolled cities and towns. The election campaign was one of the bloodiest ever in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, with leftist guerrillas and right-wing death squads killing five mayoral candidates and 19 city council candidates. Hundreds of other political activists were slain. Leftist guerrillas kidnapped 14 mayors in the two weeks before the election, then freed them after telling each to do more for the poor. <PERSON> Pastrana </PERSON>, who called for stronger action against the multibillion-dollar cocaine and marijuana trade, was kidnapped by drug traffickers in January. A week later, police acting on a tip raided a farmhouse where he was held and rescued him unharmed. One group, the <ORGANIZATION> Medellin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cartel </ORGANIZATION>, is said to be responsible for 80 percent of the cocaine smuggled into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> is charged in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> with being one of its leaders.
