<HEAD>PLO Observer Says He Will Refuse to Close Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> observer said Monday he will defy <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s decision to shut the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> mission to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said they would not try to close it immediately. <PERSON> Zehdi </PERSON> <PERSON> Labib </PERSON> <PERSON> Terzi </PERSON> said <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> authorities would have to `` put me behind steel bars'' if they wanted to close the mission, which is in a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> townhouse. `` We have the right to stay here and we will stay where we are,'' he told a news conference, and added that if the mission is closed the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> should exclude <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> from debates on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. Last Friday, Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> said he would have to close the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> observer mission as required by a new anti-terrorist law. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials said Monday another session of the 159-member <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> was possible this week in an effort to retaliate or thwart <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plans. The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> mission was established 13 years ago. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said they would not physically close it by March 21, as stipulated in the law, but would let legal proceedings run their course. The legal situation was confused. <PERSON> Terzi </PERSON> said he opposes <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> action in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts because the dispute is between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. `` Unless I am dragged, I see no reason why I should appear in a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> court,'' he told reporters. <PERSON> Terzi </PERSON> added, however, that a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen might sue in an American court to keep the mission open and protect constitutional rights of free speech and association. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> recognizes the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> as the sole legitimate representative of the <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> people and it has non-voting observer status. Its representatives have the right to address every <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> debate on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> considers the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> a terrorist organization. If the mission is forced to close and the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> message can not be heard, <PERSON> Terzi </PERSON> said, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> should decide `` in a sense of fairness and justice'' to exclude <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> debates. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> have said the decision to close the mission violates the international <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Headquarters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> under which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> allows <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> missions to operate. At a three-day emergency session Feb. 29-March 2, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> condemned <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plans to close the mission, asked the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to rule on arbitration and urged the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to abide by the Headquarters Treaty. It passed the resolution of condemnation overwhelmingly, with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> not participating, and decided to reconvene before March 21 to decide what to do if <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> decided to press ahead with closing the mission. General Assembly resolutions carry moral weight as expressions of world opinion but are not binding, as are those of the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>.
