<HEAD>Lawyers Unsuccessfully Urge Judge To Separate Husbands' Trial From
Wives'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The judge in the case of seven revolutionaries accused of plotting the overthrow of the government refused a defense request Monday to let the three women defendants be tried separately from their husbands. Ruling on pretrial motions, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> also rejected the defendants' request to dismiss the case because of what they claimed was the vagueness of the sedition statute under which they were charged. However, the judge gave the defense a victory when he indicated that witnesses who had been hypnotized to help them recall events related to the case might not be allowed to testify. Jury selection was slated to begin Tuesday. The trial is expected to last up to a year. The so-called <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> 7 face one count each of seditious conspiracy, racketeering conspiracy and racketeering enterprise. Each count carries a maximum penalty of 20 years in prison and $ 20,000 in fines. The indictment accuses defendants <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Luc </PERSON> <PERSON> Levasseur </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Manning </PERSON> of nearly 20 bombings and 10 robberies throughout the <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> since 1975 to raise money to finance their radical political aims. Two others, <PERSON> Jaan </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Laaman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, allegedly joined them on later crimes. The wives of three defendants _ <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gros </PERSON> <PERSON> Levasseur </PERSON>, <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Manning </PERSON> and <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Curzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Laaman </PERSON> _ are accused of harboring their husbands as fugitives, using false identification and taking part in some bombings. Ms. <PERSON> Lev