<HEAD>Brain-Absent Infant Still on Life-Support</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOMA LINDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A baby born with most of his brain missing clung to life Monday at a hospital where doctors hoped to make the doomed infant's organs available for transplant, a hospital spokeswoman said. `` He shows progressive signs of brain stem deterioriation but has not yet met all the criteria for total brain death,'' said <PERSON> Anita </PERSON> <PERSON> Rockwell </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> Loma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Linda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. The boy, identified only as Baby D, was born at an unidentified <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> hospital March 10 with a fatal birth defect known as anencephaly, in which much of the brain and skull are missing. The newborn's other vital organs are healthy, and his parents asked that their child be considered an organ donor. He was transferred to <PERSON> Loma </PERSON> <PERSON> Linda </PERSON>. <PERSON> Loma </PERSON> <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> has developed the nation's first medical guidelines for preserving anencephalics' heart and other vital organs for transplanting into critically ill infants. The baby is the fourth brain-absent newborn accepted at <LOCATION> Loma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Linda </LOCATION> for possible use as an organ donor. Under criteria established by the hospital, <ORGANIZATION> Baby </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> D </ORGANIZATION> was placed on life-support systems for a seven-day period, which ends Thursday night. If doctors determine that Baby D is brain-dead during that period, the hospital will serve notice that the organs are available for transplant. If the infant is not declared brain-dead within seven days, Baby D will be taken off the respirator and will be allowed to die naturally. The guidelines were developed to address ethical questions surrounding use of doomed anencephalics as organ donors. <PERSON> Loma </PERSON> <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> received nationwide attention and criticism in 1984 when Dr. <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> transplanted a baboon's heart into a girl known as Baby Fae. She died 20 -LCB- days later. <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> later transplanted infant hearts successfully. However, a shortage organ donors led <ORGANIZATION> Loma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Linda </ORGANIZATION> to develop its policy on anencephalic infants.
