<HEAD>Rodino Became A House Institution As He Helped Write History</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Retransmitting a0804 to add `p' category code.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Rodino Retirement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In 1948, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON> left his native <LOCATION> Italian </LOCATION> neighborhood in <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, an eager 38-year-old lawyer ready to represent the bustling city in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON> became an institution in the intervening 40 years: fighting for liberal legislation, controlling one of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' most powerful committees and helping write into history the downfall of a president. On Monday, the 78-year-old congressman announced his plans to retire after 20 terms. In those years, <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> decayed from the heart of the Garden State into the brunt of jokes. <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON>'s political base eroded, too. His decision not to seek re-election came in the face of mounting pressure from black political leaders, who claim it's now their time to represent the vastly changed area. Born in 1909, the son of an Italian immigrant toolmaker, <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON> seemed awed by responsibility when he was placed in charge of the President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s impeachment proceedings in 1974. `` If fate had been looking for one of the powerhouses of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, it would n't have picked me,'' he told a reporter then. But <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON>'s steady, judicious handling of the momentous hearings earned him widespread praise and helped produce an overwhelming bipartisan majority in favor of impeachment. <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON> said last year he retired to a private office and cried after his committee approved three articles of impeachment, forcing <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> to resign two weeks later. More recently, <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON> was again in on the making of history, as a senior member of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iran-Contra </ORGANIZATION> committee that investigated the sale of arms to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and the funneling of profits to the <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> Contra rebels. He had harsh words for what he called the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's lack of concern for the Constitution. He has continually used the <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to press for civil rights and what he calls `` the rule of law.'' Little in the early years of <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON>'s career suggested he might climb to the center stage of national political life. A child of the Depression, he completed law school in 1937, after 10 years of night classes. He was later decorated for World War II Army service in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. Like many members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON> relied upon service to his constituents for his electoral success. But he was a strong civil rights advocate, and that served him well as his once-prosperous city became predominantly black by the 1970s. He spoke proudly of his Italian heritage, and sponsored legislation that made Columbus Day part of a three-day annual holiday. `` <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON> was an unknown quantity,'' former <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON>, D-Mass., once recalled `` He was a flame under a bushel basket.'' <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s political demise raised <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON>'s stock considerably. He made the cover of national news magazines, starred on the dinner circuit, and was even interviewed to be <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s running mate in 1976. In December 1980, his wife and high-school sweetheart, <PERSON> Marianna </PERSON> <PERSON> Stango </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON>, died after suffering for two years from a brain tumor. <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON> had missed many a House session caring for her. He received further blows in 1982 and 1983 when he lost his brother, sister and mother-in-law. <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON> focused himself on his work, running for his seat and winning, despite ever-mounting challenges. Two years ago, he hinted he would step down as soon as <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> left office. He said then he would concentrate on writing his memoirs.
