<HEAD>Savage Fire Declared Under Control, But Cattle Low on Forage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, `Gov. Bill ...' with two grafs to UPDATE
with disaster proclamation, availability of federal aid; SUBS 11th
graf pvs, `The Federal ...' to CLARIFY that aid will be
reimbursement of firefighting costs.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A wildfire that charred hundreds of square miles of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> prairie, killing cattle and wildlife, was declared under control Monday, but surviving animals faced possible starvation without forage or feed. Federal and state officials were organizing a hay donation program for cattle roaming past burned fenceposts through the blackened terrain. Officials declared the five-county fire under control Monday about noon, said <PERSON> Murry </PERSON> <PERSON> Fly </PERSON>, the state <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s head of operations for fire control. But the forecast called for continuing dry, windy weather. Damage was so widespread that crews were still trying to assess it five days after flames from burning trash went out of control near <LOCATION> Abilene </LOCATION>. Hundreds of firefighters, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guardsmen </ORGANIZATION> and state and federal workers contained the blaze after three days. The burned swath covered parts of an area 56 miles long and 24 miles wide. `` There's been a tremendous amount of forage lost right now,'' Fly said. Lt. Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Hobby </PERSON> issued a disaster proclamation Monday, freeing up state money to help the area clean up and recover, said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Couch </PERSON> of the governor's Emergency Management Division. Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Clements </PERSON> was out of state. <PERSON> Bashur </PERSON> said representatives of the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> will instruct local officials Tuesday on how individuals can apply for relief grants from the federal government. In about 87,000 acres surveyed so far, more than 100 cattle were killed or had to be destroyed, said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Winkler </PERSON>, agriculture extension agent in <LOCATION> Shackelford </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, the hardest-hit county with more than 250,000 acres burned. An additional 175 head were injured. Wildlife in the area also suffered, he said. A herd of about 20 antelope perished in the flames, according to ranchers who answered questions about damage as they put in requests for hay and feed to keep their livestock alive. There is a two-day supply of donated feed on hand, <PERSON> Winkler </PERSON> said. Ranchers without winter forage for their herds will have to sell their livestock, haul in hay or feed, or truck the cattle elsewhere, he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> will make disaster aid available to reimburse firefighting costs in the five-county region, said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Miles </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> director. If ranchers had to buy feed for all 15,000 cattle affected by the fire, it would require 175 tons a day, at a daily cost of $ 30,000, said <PERSON> Winkler </PERSON>. Over the weekend, ranchers from across <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> began donating hay. By Sunday, tractor-trailers stacked with hay rolls were parked on the courthouse square in <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>. At least seven firefighters were treated for minor injuries, said Fly. The wildfire at one point threatened the towns of <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> and <PERSON> Baird </PERSON>.
