<HEAD>The Queen of Ranchera Music</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER PICHARDINI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 All you have to say in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> Lola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> la </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION>, or <PERSON> Lola </PERSON> the Great One, and everyone knows who you're talking about <PERSON> Lola </PERSON> is <PERSON> Lola </PERSON> <PERSON> Beltran </PERSON>, the queen of ranchera music, whose rich, husky and wide-ranged voice can evoke the pain and happiness of love, tender feelings for the land or the gaiety of a Mexican fiesta. For 35 years, <PERSON> Beltran </PERSON> has shared those sounds of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> throughout the world, often bringing tears to the eyes of homesick Mexicans in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and elsewhere. `` My soul feels like crying. ... I need you so much and yet I swore I would never tell you this,'' she sang in one of her first concerts after she made a hit on <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> XEW radio station. `` Three days without looking at you ... three days crying for you ... three days looking at the sunrise,'' she sang in another song, this one written by a friend _ composer <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON>, the sad-faced, tragic figure of modern Mexican music who died an early death and who became famous for songs about love, land, bars and drink. `` I will always remember <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Beltran </PERSON> said, recalling the times they performed together in Mexican films. `` Since he died, many beautiful things have disappeared. He was unique and extraordinary. Only those who go to heaven can have his kind of heart.'' <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON> wrote the lyrics that broke down barriers and appealed to pure, raw, feelings. `` What can you know about life? When did you ever open with me the doors to <PERSON> Tenampa </PERSON>?'' which is a popular <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> mariachi bar. On March 12, <PERSON> Beltran </PERSON> was honored in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Hispanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION>. The honor came as the sounds of `` ranchera'' music gets new, widespread attention in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from pop singer <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Ronstadt </PERSON> and her Spanish-language album `` Canciones de Mi Padre,'' or `` Songs of My Father.'' <PERSON> Ronstadt </PERSON>, who was recently in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> rehearsing for her current concert tour of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said she always has been an admirer of the regal <PERSON> Beltran </PERSON>. `` When I was growing up, my father used to play the records of <PERSON> Lola </PERSON> <PERSON> Beltran </PERSON>, who has always been a great influence on my singing,'' <PERSON> Ronstadt </PERSON> recalled. `` I love that young girl,'' <PERSON> Beltran </PERSON> said. `` Whenever I am in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, she comes to see me and when she comes here, I am happy to receive her.'' <PERSON> Beltran </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ronstadt </PERSON> performed a duet last fall at the <ORGANIZATION> Acapulco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION>. `` I am very grateful to everyone,'' <PERSON> Beltran </PERSON> said in an interview. `` I have been lucky enough to sing for people like -LRB- Presidents -RRB- <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> and -LRB- former <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaulle </PERSON>.'' Like most music of the people, `` ranchera'' music is similar to American country music, with a few Mexican variations. `` May the devil take you, you murderous bull,'' <PERSON> Beltran </PERSON> curses in a soulful song that recounts the death of a young boy who sneaks into the corrals and is killed by the brave bulls under a moonlit night. Since <PERSON> Beltran </PERSON>'s first three songs on XEW, she has maded more than 100 albums and acted in more than 50 movies. However, she is not as active as she used to be years ago when she would sing before a weekly TV audience or in between cockfights. But she does three benefits every year and has an invitation to sing at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> next May.
