<HEAD>Demise of the Deux Chevaux, a French Automotive Institution</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For nearly half a century, mountains, deserts and <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>' traffic could n't stop it _ that chugging, ungainly four-wheeled beast known as the <ORGANIZATION> Deux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chevaux </ORGANIZATION>. But modern times have, and an era in the French auto industry has come to an end. The Deux Chevaux -LRB- French for two horses, or two horsepower -RRB- is a car, although some say it is an exaggeration to call it that _ tin can on wheels is more like it. The last one rolled off a <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> assembly line Feb. 29 when <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s oldest automobile factory, the Citroen plant in <LOCATION> Levallois </LOCATION>, shut down. There was hardly a whimper or a word in the press. Yet the closing of the plant on the western edge of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> signals the demise of the tortoise-shaped automotive with bulging headlights that look like a frog's eyes. So ends an institution as French as the beret or baguette. Whether rattling down a country road or careening across a city boulevard, with its side windows flapping on their hinges, the <ORGANIZATION> Deux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chevaux </ORGANIZATION> has long been part of the French landscape. Its snail's pace and its noisy chugs have endeared millions, spawning <ORGANIZATION> Deux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chevaux </ORGANIZATION> fan clubs worldwide `` When the last car left the factory in <LOCATION> Levallois </LOCATION>, you can say it was the end of an era,'' said <PERSON> Gro </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoeg </PERSON>, a Citroen spokeswoman. `` But you ca n't say it is the end of the <ORGANIZATION> Deux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chevaux </ORGANIZATION>.'' The car will continue to be manufactured in <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, but at less than half the 1987 rate, when 43,255 <PERSON> Deux </PERSON> <PERSON> Chevaux </PERSON> were turned out. `` I do n't have great patriotic sentiment, but it's the only car with a French identity,'' said three-time <ORGANIZATION> Deux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chevaux </ORGANIZATION> owner <PERSON> Gilles </PERSON> <PERSON> Collignon </PERSON>. The <PERSON> Deux </PERSON> <PERSON> Chevaux </PERSON> was conceived as an affordable car for those of modest means. When it first came out the <ORGANIZATION> Deux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chevaux </ORGANIZATION> cost the franc equivalent of about $ 650. The two latest models cost $ 6,500 and $ 7,460. Like sensible shoes, the buggy with bed-spring suspension, a simple engine, no `` extras,'' is functional in the extreme. And allegedly indestructible. Funny looking to some people, downright ugly to others, the <ORGANIZATION> Deux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chevaux </ORGANIZATION> is simply `` beyond beauty,'' says Citroen. In the 1960s, <ORGANIZATION> Deux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chevaux </ORGANIZATION>'s heyday, it became a reverse status symbol among the rebellious young. `` It's more than a car,'' said <PERSON> Collignon </PERSON>. `` Everyone who has one has a more or less sentimental relationship with it. `` The big advantage is that it can be completely falling apart, broken all over, and it keeps running. It has an incredible life.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Deux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chevaux </ORGANIZATION> has set altitude and depth records for a car _ climbing to 17,180 feet on <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chacaltaya </LOCATION> in 1953 and down deep into a salt mine in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Lorraine </PERSON> region. Two Frenchmen, <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Seguela </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Baudot </PERSON>, made an 87,000-mile round-the-world trip in a <LOCATION> Deux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chevaux </LOCATION>, once resorting to crushed bananas to replace oil lost from a broken gearbox during a 200-mile desert stretch. `` Four wheels under an umbrella'' was the order to engineers working on the design in the 1930s, according to <ORGANIZATION> Citroen </ORGANIZATION>, which later touted it as `` the most minimum car.'' A wooden model was produced in 1936. World War II intervened, and the car was not formally unveiled until October 1948 at the Paris Auto show. Originally available only in gray, with a top speed of 37 miles an hour, today's <PERSON> Deux </PERSON> <PERSON> Chevaux </PERSON> streak by in all colors, or even two-tone, and can reach a top speed of 72 mph. The upgraded engine remains mechanically elementary and the horsepower has increased from two to three. Citroen brochures call the <ORGANIZATION> Deux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chevaux </ORGANIZATION> `` a mechanical phenomenon, a commercial phenomenon, a sociological phenomenon.'' But the truth, Ms. <PERSON> Hoeg </PERSON> concedes, is that the car is outmoded. `` Orders have fallen a lot,'' she said in a telephone interview. `` The European market is increasingly closed to the <ORGANIZATION> Deux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chevaux </ORGANIZATION> because of pollution norms.'' Strict pollution controls, for example, have effectively banned the car from <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> since October 1987. It has not been sold in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> since 1968 and in <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> since 1982 because it does n't come up to their safety standards. <ORGANIZATION> Deux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chevaux </ORGANIZATION> fans in other countries are expected to be deprived of the car in the coming years, Ms. <PERSON> Hoeg </PERSON> said. No effort was ever made to sell it in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but she said she understands there are some Deux Chevaux collectors there. The closing of the <LOCATION> Levallois </LOCATION> plant, built in 1893, is part of an overall retrenchment of the French auto industry. At its peak in the mid-1960s, the plant turned out 550 <ORGANIZATION> Deux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chevaux </ORGANIZATION> a day, compared to 80 a day last year. The Citroen plant in <LOCATION> Manguade </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, manufacturing <ORGANIZATION> Deux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chevaux </ORGANIZATION> since 1982, is expected to produce about 20,000 in 1988.
