<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Guinness, Adv 17,0838</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thu AMs, March 17 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Walk In The Zoo With An Actor-Knight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Hello dear. You're very handsome. Yes you are,'' Sir <PERSON> Alec </PERSON> <PERSON> Guinness </PERSON> coos through the cage at a rhinoceros. `` You've got a sweet face, very pretty ears,'' the elder statesman of British acting says, as he strolls through <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s central <PERSON> Zoologischen </PERSON> <PERSON> Garten </PERSON> His chat with the animals is almost as engaging as the wonderful characters he has portrayed on stage and screen during five decades as one of the world's finest, most chameleon-like talents. On this particular day, the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Film Festival was awarding the 73-year-old Guinness its special `` Ehren Bear'' -LRB- honorary bear -RRB- for lifetime achievement in the cinema. The actor, however, elected to avoid the morning crush of screenings and news conferences for a romp in the zoo. `` I'm not actually that keen on them; I hate to see certain animals caged up,'' he said. `` But I remember this zoo being small and very imaginatively laid out on the open plan, and I thought it might be amusing to have a second look.'' He last visited the <PERSON> Zoologischen </PERSON> <PERSON> Garten </PERSON> 14 years ago. Images of some of the zoo's reported stock of 10,000 animals have lingered: `` They used to have white rhinoceroses there that were charming. And a great sea lion covered in shrapnel wounds _ an old thing that was like a symbol of <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>; a splendid, great creature.'' This time around, <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION>' observations are as keen as ever, whether applied to the varieties of zoo-bound species or the special tributes that have marked his career. In 1980, he received a special Academy Award to honor a range of work encompassing such portrayals as the sinister <PERSON> Fagin </PERSON> in `` Oliver Twist'' -LRB- 1948 -RRB-, a comic octet of murder victims in `` Kind Hearts and Coronets'' -LRB- 1950 -RRB-, the hard-driving Colonel <PERSON> Nicholson </P