PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Waugh </PERSON>'s 1934 novel, `` A Handful of Dust.'' Then there's <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Blessing </PERSON>'s current Broadway play, `` A Walk in the <PERSON> Woods </PERSON>,'' which Guinness may do on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> stage. He last trod the West End boards in <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>'s `` The Old Country'' in 1977-8. `` It's a very distinguished piece of writing,'' he says of the play. But Guinness acknowledges its pitfalls, as well: `` The amount of learning for a two-hander is horrendous. An actor's great fear is that he wo n't have the memory.'' On that topic, he is emboldened by the recent return to the stage, after a decade away, of his friend and mentor, Sir <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gielgud </PERSON>, in the new play `` The Best of Friends.'' `` <PERSON> Gielgud </PERSON> is 83,'' <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> says matter-of-factly, `` and he got through it -LRB- the play -RRB- very successfully.'' By now, the sky has clouded over, and rain looks likely. Guinness has a lunch date for which he must n't be late, so he returns to his hotel to find that autograph hunters have arrived. `` There they are,'' he says, sounding resigned as the anonymity of the walk in the zoo gives way to the fans' ever-ready pens and cameras. But before leaving the zoo, he has one last remark about rhinos: `` We're told they have very nice personalities.'' He takes an inimitable pause. `` But I do n't think I'd like to encounter them intimately.''
