<HEAD>The Name Lavrenti Beria Still Brings Chills to Soviets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Spelling ``Sergo'' correct start of 14th graf.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lavrenti </PERSON> <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>. The mere mention of the name stills brings chills to some Soviets. In the 1960s, years after his death, people still avoided walking past his drab mansion at 28 <ORGANIZATION> Kachalov </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> because of the terrible memories it might evoke. Now, 34 years after <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>'s own execution, the mansion houses the <ORGANIZATION> Tunisian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Abderraouf </PERSON> <PERSON> Ounaies </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION> said there were stories that <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> had a dungeon built in the basement and a secret passageway. Some areas of the basement could have been used as a dungeon, <PERSON> Ounaies </PERSON> said, but he found no evidence of that they actually were used for that, nor was there evidence of a secret passageway. The curse seems to have worn off. People these days walk by, apparently without giving a thought to <PERSON> Lavrenti </PERSON> <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>, the balding, small Georgian who wore pince-nez and is held responsible for the executions of millions during the Stalin era. `` Every generation has its horrors,'' said an elderly neighborhood woman, who recalled seeing <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> strolling outside the mansion when he lived there. The administration of General Secretary <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> says it wants the current generation of Soviets to know the truth about the past, and is reviving nightmares about <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> and the machine of terror he ran in the late 1930s and 1940s as <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s most ruthless and powerful henchman Press articles and the portrayal of a Beria-Hitler-like character in the recent Georgian movie `` Repentance'' are part of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s attempts to fill in `` blank spots'' in history _ formerly taboo subjects. He believes that extending his policy of glasnost, or openness, to the crimes of the <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> era will help ensure that such mistakes are not repeated. The effort parallels <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s drive to rid Soviet society of Stalinist policies under which the central government exercised tight control over the economy. <PERSON> Sergo </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikoyan </PERSON>, the son of the late <PERSON> Anastas </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikoyan </PERSON> who had served with <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> in the <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> leadership, wrote Feb. 21 in the youth newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Komsomolskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION> that it is important to review <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> `` to finally free the future from the past.'' <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>'s legacy is the image of the state security forces as all-powerful and ruthless. In their re-examination of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>, Soviet media have not touched on this image as it pertains to the present-day <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION>, successor to <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> NKVD </ORGANIZATION>. Also conspicuously absent is any criticism of the system that enabled such a pair to take charge and to operate their machine of terror for so long. This is not the first time the official media have focused on <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>'s reign of terror. He was first exposed during <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>'s de-Stalinization drive in the 1950s and 60s. <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>, in his memoirs _ published only in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> _ called <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> `` a butcher and an assassin,'' a `` beast'' who was `` without the slightest trace of human decency'' and who was `` very skillful at anything that was filthy and treacherous.'' Although <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> was sharply condemned during <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>'s years, the early official accounts inacurrately described his relationship with <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>. `` We refused to believe that <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> himself could have been behind the terror which <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> oversaw,'' <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> wrote. `` For a while, we gave the party and the people incorrect explanations about what had happened; we blamed everything on <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>. He was a convenient figure.'' The truth, <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> said, was that `` <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> did n't create <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>; <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> created <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>.'' Only now, under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, is the official record being corrected, with the help of <PERSON> Sergo </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikoyan </PERSON> and the sons of other members of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s Politburo, <PERSON> Georgy </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Malenkov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Malenkov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> are quoted in a recent edition of <LOCATION> Nedelya </LOCATION>, a weekly supplement to the <ORGANIZATION> Literary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazette </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. That and the other articles put the blame squarely on <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>. `` I believe that the roots of <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>'s evil deeds should be sought in the personality of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> rather than in <LOCATION> Beria </LOCATION> himself,'' <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhusyenin </PERSON> wrote in <LOCATION> Nedelya </LOCATION>. `` Namely the cult, the deviation from Leninist norms, resulted in the <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> phenomenon. <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> was able to guess <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s wishes, was able to exploit the weaknesses of his master for personal profit and self-glorification.'' <PERSON> Zhusyenin </PERSON> said that when he interviewed people, `` their arms began to tremble at the very mention of the name <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>.''
