<HEAD>MOSCOW: name Beria.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The writers of the recent articles said they had trouble researching <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> because he did such a good job of covering his tracks, making sure that any evidence that could be used against him was destroyed and witnesses killed. <ORGANIZATION> Komsomolskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION> stated the new evaluation of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s relationship with <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> in its headline over <PERSON> Sergo </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikoyan </PERSON>'s article: `` The Servant <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> tapped <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>, a fellow Georgian, to be deputy head of the already-dreaded <ORGANIZATION> NKVD </ORGANIZATION>, as the state security and police force was known at the time, in the summer of 1938. By year's end, <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> replaced <ORGANIZATION> NKVD </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Yezhov </PERSON>, who had fallen out of favor with <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> and was executed in 1940. The people breathed a sigh of relief, hoping that the years of bloody mass purges were behind them. Mass arrests did end, but the terror continued. <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> simply made it more selective, playing on <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s paranoia by identifying and eliminating those deemed to be `` enemies of the people.'' In the meantime, he garnered a staggering amount of power. <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> became the first secret police chief elevated to the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s ruling Politburo. During World War II, <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> named <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> to the committee supervising defense and later put him in charge of developing a Soviet atomic bomb. After the war, <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> controlled the regular and secret police, the country's labor camps, propaganda and transport, as well as a private empire in his native <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and surrounding regions. Among the horrors Western historians link to <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> was the massacre of more than 4,000 Polish officers in the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Smolensk </LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION> NKVD </ORGANIZATION> troops in April 1940. The official Soviet version is that the Poles were killed by Germans. On a personal level, Soviet accounts of <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> said he interrogated and executed prisoners himself. <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> claimed <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> raped teen-age girls after having them kidnapped off the streets. <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>'s intrigues also took a heavy toll on the party itself. <PERSON> Nedyelya </PERSON> noted that <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> collected files on every government leader, including <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, for possible use against them. His victims included veteran party members, comrades-in-arms of V.I. <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> and officials of the party youth group <ORGANIZATION> Komsomol </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Nedyelya </PERSON> said. Even <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> began to fear <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>, and by 1946 had taken away all his henchman's security posts. But <PERSON> Beria </PERSON> retained unofficial control over the security organs, and planned to use his forces to seize power after <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s death in March 1953. <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>, in his memoirs and in remarks cited Feb. 24 in <ORGANIZATION> Literary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazette </ORGANIZATION>, said he was aware of <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>'s ambitions and suggested privately to the other top leaders in the summer of 1953 that they oust <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>. They agreed. The Politburo, in <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>'s presence, met and voted to arrest him Military troops outside <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>'s control took him to prison. He was put on trial, convicted of being a British agent _ a dubious charge _ and of trying to `` elevate the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> above the party and government in order to seize power.'' Official accounts say he was executed Dec. 23, 1953, but some Western historians believe he was put to death months earlier. <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>, who had been in the limelight for 14 years, quickly became a non-person. The editors of the official Soviet encyclopedia, for example, told readers to paste an article about the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> over one about <PERSON> Beria </PERSON>.
