<HEAD>Military Still a Political Force in Honduras</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the farmworkers union failed to persuade civilian officials to remove <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Espinal </PERSON> as head of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agrarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, it took its case to the armed forces chief. In going to Gen. <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Regalado </PERSON> and the military high command the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Honduran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campesinos </ORGANIZATION> made plain its feeling, shared by others, that real power in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> does not lie with the civilian government of President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Azcono </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON>. The union is seeking <PERSON> Espinal </PERSON>'s ouster from the Cabinet-level post on grounds that he was stalling on agrarian reform. <PERSON> Espinal </PERSON>, nevertheless, remains in his post, confirmed once again by <PERSON> Azcono </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON>, and so far as is known <PERSON> Regalado </PERSON> has not acted. The campesinos' tactic was also used in the past few years by bus drivers, teachers, business leaders and other sectors. It underscores the powerful, even dominant, role still exercised by the armed forces six years after <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> restored civilian government. <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> has a long history of military governments, most recently in the 1972-82 period. `` The people know where the source of power lies,'' said <PERSON> Anibal </PERSON> <PERSON> Puerto </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and a critic of <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON>'s administration. Even government supporters acknowledge the imbalance of power. `` Longstanding vices are not gotten rid of from the night to the morning,'' said <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luna </PERSON> <PERSON> Mejia </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Honduran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Private </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION>. In an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, he said consolidation of civilian power `` is coming along well.'' But he also observed, `` Here, as in all countries, interests are managed according to the real powers. And if those powers are ambitious, we could fall again into old vices.'' `` No Honduran politician is going around saying, ` We've got to put the military back in the box,' because here the military never has been in the box,'' said a Western diplomat. Compared to its neighbors, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> has enjoyed a degree of stability and peace during a decade of regional conflict. But the civil wars surrounding it have caused big problems. `` We have become a sanctuary,'' said <PERSON> Luna </PERSON> <PERSON> Mejia </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>' tens of thousands of refugees from <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, all torn by guerrilla wars `` We are victims of the entry into our country of irregular forces.'' He referred to the Contras, who since 1982 have been trying to topple the Sandinista government in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. Until last year, a Contra force estimated at 6,000 to 12,000 men had waged the better part of the campaign from base camps in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> along the Nicaraguan border. The rebels say most of their forces are now inside <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. By congressional vote, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has cut off further military aid, damaging prospects for long-term effectiveness inside <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. `` There is a great concern that the Contras, if defeated, will try to come back here,'' said <PERSON> Luna </PERSON> <PERSON> Mejia </PERSON>. Gen. <PERSON> Regalado </PERSON> told journalists in February he hoped the Contras would be able to keep up their fight but said if they can not, they are not welcome back in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. `` We have instructed immigration authorities along the border to ensure that they do not return,'' he said. Puerto sees a connection between the Contra problem and continued military preponderance in Honduran politics. Citing <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>' very strong alliance with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, he said: `` To whom does the Honduran army owe its allegiance? Everything indicates it owes its allegiance to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and not to its own people.'' He said civilian government and close alignment with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had done little to alleviate the poverty of hundreds of thousands in this mainly agricultural country of 4.5 million people. `` People expected something different from civilian government, but they got more of the same,'' Puerto said. `` If things continue like this, people may lose faith in so-called democracy and look for other less desirable forms of struggle.'' <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON> is past the midway point in the four-year term to which he was inaugurated in January 1986. Elections are scheduled in November 1989.
</TEXT>
