<FIRST>s w BC-APN--AirlineTurmoil Adv27-2Takes   03-14 1017</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Airline Turmoil, Adv 27-2 Takes,1046</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv27</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 27</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&amp;w
photos and 1 graphic.)</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Labor relations in the airline industry used to be fairly genteel and mutual accommodation was the rule. Then, after deregulation, came a competitive crunch, mergers and cost-cutting, and at many carriers snarl has replaced purr. A reporter surveys today's turbulent scene.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> and several senior executives are fired after a closed-door deal with the airline's labor unions. Flight attendants trek to the suburban home of the chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> to register a protest about a strike that ended nearly two years ago. More than 4,000 of them are still looking to get their jobs back. <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, expecting a strike, is planning for a small cargo carrier with non-union pilots to fly many of its passenger planes, prompting charges of union busting from <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> pilots and mechanics. It's management and labor hardball, pure and simple. And it has become more frequent since the government eased out of regulating the airline industry in the early 1980s. Along with bitter competition among airlines have come increasingly acrimonious relations with labor. In the wars between airline workers and their bosses, the genteel atmosphere of bargaining _ common when the government had its reins on the industry _ seems to have gone the way of the propeller airplane. The hotbed of labor-management combat is at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, the Miami-based airline that has struggled with huge losses and almost continuous labor turmoil for more than a decade. The company wants major concessions. The unions say they're being pushed into a strike. When word came recently that 26 Eastern jets were being leased to a little known cargo operator named <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, the news unleashed a firestorm among many of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s employees. It was no secret that <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, in the midst of stormy contract talks with its mechanics, intends in event of a strike this summer to have non-union <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> pilots fly the leased planes on <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s most critical routes. `` It's an attempt to decimate <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s cockpit crews,'' says <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Bavis </PERSON>, head of the airline's pilots union. There are hints from the parent 40,000-member <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> of a one-day nationwide shutdown of air service if Eastern ever uses the Orion pilots. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president for human relations, calls the non-union <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> pilots `` our insurance coverage.'' Corporate hardball. `` Prior to deregulation, for maybe 20 years, there was a posture of accommodation. The unions accepted the companies and the companies accepted the unions. Government generally was neutral or slightly on the side of labor,'' says <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Cassels </PERSON>, a professor of industrial relations at <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. When labor wanted more money, the airlines often agreed. They knew that the government would pass the increased costs on in the form of higher fares. Today, airlines compete vigorously on fares and have argued that one of their biggest problems has been high labor costs. On average, 35 percent of airline operational costs are for labor, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. As a result, there has been `` a stage of outright hostility'' between labor and management in recent years, <PERSON> Cassels </PERSON> says. The tiff at Eastern may be the latest, but it's hardly the most bitter standoff between labor and management in recent years. It was in September 1983 that <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the nemesis of airline labor, stopped negotiating with the unions and shut down <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. He declared bankruptcy and shed the existing labor contracts. Three days later, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> emerged with pilots flying the same planes, but earning half the salary. Pilots and flight attendants saw their strike fizzle. Today, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, which like <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> is owned by <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, is larger than ever, but many of its one-time well-paid pilots are wearing the uniforms of other airlines and have lost much of their seniority and pay. In early 1986 the flight attendants at <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>, faced with demands for sharp salary cuts, walked off their jobs and onto the picket lines. Today two-thirds of the 6,500 attendants who went on strike are still grounded. While the attendants await a recall from <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>, the airline continues to fly with a third fewer attendants who earn less money and work longer hours. Would the flight attendants again choose a strike? <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON> <PERSON> Frankovich </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Attendants </ORGANIZATION>, who led the 1986 walkout, mulls the question over before answering. `` I do n't think we had a choice,'' she says. Attendants at other airlines may not have lost their jobs in recent years, but they have not been able to exert much clout. Recently, flight attendants were pushed reluctantly into a settlement at American and thought better of a strike at <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION>, where negotiations continue. But labor _ at least in terms of the more-powerful pilots and mechanics unions _ has flexed its muscles as well after several years of back-pedaling and reeling from management demands. Consider the fired <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> executives. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, with the blessing of fellow members of the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> board of directors, resigned and sealed the deal with a handshake last January. He then walked into the office of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Acker </PERSON> and informed <PERSON> Acker </PERSON> and Vice Chairman <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Shugrue </PERSON> they were fired. By the time the bloodletting was over, three senior vice presidents, including <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Grebey </PERSON>, who was in charge of labor relations, also were forced to resign. <PERSON> Acker </PERSON> is now in <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION> `` assessing what he's going to do next.'' <PERSON> Shugrue </PERSON> recently was hired by <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to head its <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON> can understand how they feel. A former hotel executive, <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON> had a dream of turning <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> into a broad-based travel company. While at the helm of <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, he bought two hotel chains and a rental car company and envisioned one-stop shopping for transportation and lodging for businessmen.
</TEXT>
