<FIRST>s w BC-APN--AirlineTurmoil Adv27-1stAdd   03-14 0876</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Airline Turmoil, Adv 27-1st Add,0901</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv27</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 27</NOTE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: for businessmen.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The name of <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, was changed to <ORGANIZATION> Allegis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, to broaden its appeal, but the moniker never caught on among Wall Street investors. It also served to highlight claims by the pilots that <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON> was siphoning money and attention from the airline. One evening last June, the company's board of directors demanded <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON>' resignation. The pilots claimed responsibility. Although <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON>' fall may have been the result of a variety of forces, most industry analysts agree that his empire began to fail when the pilots union launched a $ 4.5 billion takeover bid, the first effort by a union to buy an entire airline. `` Anyone who thinks that the pilots union or the machinists today are the underdogs in one of these battles is clearly mistaken,'' says <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Onstad </PERSON>, a vice president for <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>. Indeed, pilots at many airlines have regained the momentum. Their salaries are on the upswing. The dual wage scales _ a lower one for newly hired pilots _ imposed by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> in 1983 and widely copied by other carriers is showing signs of erosion. New contracts call for a more rapid merging of the two scales. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, caught unprepared and disorganized by the <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> bankruptcy, has vowed never to be left so vulnerable again. Stiff increases in dues for its 40,000 members have brought $ 40 million into a war chest that continues to grow. The unions also say they will continue to take their fights into airline board rooms, citing their successes at <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> and at <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> where the pilots formed an unusual alliance with corporate raider <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> two years ago to fend off <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>. Ironically, that set the stage for <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> to buy <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, where labor war remains rife. Nevertheless, declares <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> president <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON>, `` Labor unions will continue to increase their Wall Street connections.'' `` Certainly in this day and age you wo n't get -LRB- salary or work rule -RRB- givebacks,'' says <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Joedicke </PERSON>, airline analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros </ORGANIZATION>. But he adds quickly that he would n't `` put the unions in the catbird seat'' just yet. Nowhere is that more true than at <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, the Houston-based airline whose <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> subsidiaries account for 20 percent of the industry's market and which has led the trend toward lower airline fares. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> made his mark in 1972 when he bought debt-ridden <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> and turned it around by unleashing `` peanut fares'' when business was slow. His low-fare strategy continued with <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Air in 1981 and with the newly emerged Continental two years later. But to play out the strategy, <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> had to cut costs, a direct attack on labor. `` Does Frank like unions? That's not the issue,'' says <PERSON> Onstad </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>'s point man in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` The issue is how does management get the flexibility to deal in a deregulated environment that <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> is dealing with.'' <PERSON> Onstad </PERSON> says that some members of the machinists union, especially ground workers who haul baggage, are earning salaries _ an average of $ 43,000 a year with fringes _ that are way too high. When <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> emerged with a non-union work force in 1983 it had cut its pilots' pay in half overnight. <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> workers in 1986 earned on average $ 28,200 a year, the lowest in the industry, and better than a third lower than its chief competitors. Mechanics at <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> earn $ 16 an hour base salary, $ 4 an hour lower than new contracts agreed to at <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>, according to the machinist union. In the third quarter of last year, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>'s labor costs were 22 percent of total operating costs, compared to about 35 percent industrywide. But <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> executives argue that low costs are needed if the airline is to survive and continue to provide the low fares that have opened air travel to millions of people. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, lost $ 466 million last year and its executives put much of the blame on costs related to absorbing <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> and the labor unrest at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, where losses were $ 182 million. Eastern president <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakes </PERSON> has said he wants $ 490 million in labor concessions at the struggling airline. Union leaders countered that they have given back too much already and accuse <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> of trying to dismember the airline. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Bavis </PERSON>, the pilot's leader at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, says that since <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> bought the airline he has: _ Sold <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s valuable computer reservation system to <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> _ Cleared the way for <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> to fly <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s profitable <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> routes if <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> chooses to _ Sold six <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> A-300s and a <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> DC-10 to <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> _ Tried to spin-off <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s moneymaking Northeast air shuttle operation under a separate subsidiary `` He's taking the crown jewels, spinning them off and making them part of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>,'' says <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, the chief of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> at Eastern. <PERSON> Onstad </PERSON> suggests the Eastern negotations have industrywide implications. `` We are now the last of the low-cost operators. People focus all of their attention on <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Onstad </PERSON> says. `` If the unions can defeat us, low fares go away and the pressure on wages at other airlines go away.''
