<SECOND>BC-APN--Literacy Quest, Adv 27,1133</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv27</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 27</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 It's been called <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s most hidden problem. An estimated one in five adults in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> ca n't read beyond the fourth-grade level. But help is available through a growing network of organizations dedicated to stamping out illiteracy. Two of the most successful groups are based in <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>, N.Y.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Everson </PERSON> always feared `` signing away his life.'' Even more, he dreaded revealing that he could n't read Then, about four years ago, <PERSON> Everson </PERSON> received a letter from a local hospital saying he owed a big bill for recent treatments. His nightmare had become reality. `` I told them I had Medicaid to take care of it, but they said I had agreed to pay the bill,'' <PERSON> Everson </PERSON> says. `` They said I had signed my name on the dotted line.'' Fortunately, the 42-year-old <PERSON> Everson </PERSON> was able to settle the dispute, but only after admitting to hospital officials that he really did n't know what he had signed because he could n't read. That was the catalyst <PERSON> Everson </PERSON> needed to seek help. No longer would <PERSON> Everson </PERSON> have to rely on his wife, children or siblings to explain service applications and contracts to him or read him the newspaper to him. Above all, he would be able to do the thing he had longed for most _ to be able to read his Bible for the sermons he gave to his Church of God in Christ congregation at <ORGANIZATION> Payton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>. Over the years, family members had read the Bible to him. `` At first it was hard, but after a while I began to know by heart most of the verses I would use in my sermons,'' the minister says. `` I might not know the exact words, but I knew the exact feeling and that was easy to translate.'' <PERSON> Everson </PERSON> says it's painful to admit you ca n't read, `` But it opens a new way of life and you have to admit it to get help.'' Living in <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>, it was easy for <PERSON> Everson </PERSON> to find help. The city is the headquarters of two of the most successful organizations in the fight against illiteracy _ <ORGANIZATION> Laubach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Literacy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Literacy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Volunteers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, both part of a national campaign being conducted by <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Literacy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- PLUS -RRB-. <PERSON> Laubach </PERSON> is the older of the two groups, founded in 1955 by the late <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Laubach </PERSON>, a missionary who spent 40 years traveling the globe teaching people how to read and write their native languages. <PERSON> Laubach </PERSON> became internationally recognized for his approach to illiteracy, the `` Laubach Method.'' Today, LLI has 750 councils in 45 states as well as an international program and publishing division. <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION> housewife <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Colvin </PERSON> was inspired by <PERSON> Laubach </PERSON>, who taught at <ORGANIZATION> Syracuse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in the 1950s, and in 1962 she began a basement organization speaking out against illiteracy and teaching people to read. Today, nearly 300 LVA community affiliates comprise a network spanning 35 states. The organization has doubled in size in the last three years. Together, the two groups are responsible for teaching millions of Americans to read. Last year alone, both estimated they taught more than 100,000 adults how to read. Sadly, that only scratches the surface. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> says 27 million adults in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ one in every five _ ca n't read beyond a fourth-grade level. In some cases the consequences have been tragic. A <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> mother fed undiluted formula to her nine-day old infant because she could n't read the directions. The baby died. The government estimates illiteracy costs the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> about $ 225 billion annually in welfare payments, lost job productivity, unrealized earnings and tax revenues and crime. While illiteracy is predominantly a problem of poor <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, its victims include bankers, real estate brokers, firefighters, farmers, laborers and others, according to <PERSON> Colvin </PERSON>. `` Do n't equate ignorance with illiteracy. People learn to get by,'' she says. `` They contrive ways to work around it because they are too embarrassed to let anyone know. Some people have remarkable memories, others fake poor eyesight and have others do their reading.'' However, the demands of today's high-tech society have made it harder. `` It's a national embarrassment,'' says <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Waite </PERSON>, director of American programs for <PERSON> Laubach </PERSON>. `` Illiteracy is <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s most hidden problem, and its most solvable problem given adequate resources. Really, there's no good reason people who want to learn how to read and write ca n't do it. There are a dozen proven programs out there now.'' <PERSON> Laubach </PERSON> and Literacy Volunteers each have their own approach to teaching. Both are self-paced individual programs that specialize in mobilizing volunteers to serve as tutors. But <PERSON> Laubach </PERSON> teaches reading through a phonics-based system keyed on letter and word sound association, while Literacy Volunteers use a four-part method that incorporates phonics. The Literacy Volunteers approach also takes advantage of language experience, using the student's hobbies or interests to draw on as a basis to teach new words. Sight words and patterned words are other reading techniques employed by Literacy Volunteers. Sight words are those so basic to reading and encountered so often that they are best learned by sight, not by sounding them out, such as ` the,' ` have,' and ` were.' In the patterned words technique, which concentrates on vowel sounds, words are taught by learning families of words, such as ` man,' ` can,' ` fan.' `` It has n't been easy, but I do n't know why I did n't try and learn sooner,'' says <PERSON> Everson </PERSON>, who wants to become an LVA tutor as soon as he becomes proficient. `` The longer you wait, the worse it gets as far as dealing with the problem. Learning to read is like finding yourself.'' <PERSON> Waite </PERSON> and <PERSON> Colvin </PERSON> say <PERSON> Everson </PERSON>'s story is a familiar one. `` It's interesting if you ask a student whose fault it is they ca n't read, invariably they will say it's their fault,'' <PERSON> Waite </PERSON> says. `` They blame themselves. But there are always extenuating circumstances they ca n't control. Someone else's fault: a teacher, a parent, a school system. They drop behind and then get caught in the cycle.'' In recent years, the federal and local governments, local school systems, libraries, churches, businesses and community groups have entered the endeavor, starting up programs at various levels to assist people in learning how to read. `` There's no indication the problem is getting any worse,'' <PERSON> Waite </PERSON> says. `` However, it does n't appear to be getting any better.''
</TEXT>
