<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ Five years after he became conductor of the City of <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Symphony </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orchestra </LOCATION> at age 25, <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Rattle </PERSON> thought it could become <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s best. At 33, he has n't changed his mind. <PERSON> Rattle </PERSON>, who is attracting a lot of attention in the world of music, is now bringing the orchestra to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to show it off in 11 cities.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Rattle </PERSON>, who has become known as one of the world's most exciting young conductors, is introducing his <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Birmingham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symphony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orchestra </ORGANIZATION> to American audiences for the first time. The orchestra, which Rattle believes is `` well on the way'' to becoming <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s finest, will tour 11 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cities from March 29 to April 17. Rattle has made his mark in the music world without joining the baton-wielding jet set or accepting a top job with a prestigious orchestra. In fact, he regularly turns down offers to appear as guest conductor. The 33-year-old native of <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, prefers to concentrate on his job as conductor of the <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> orchestra and his work as principal guest of the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Philharmonic </LOCATION>. The curly haired, bright-eyed <PERSON> Rattle </PERSON> took over the <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> orchestra in 1980, at age 25. He plans to stay a while, already making plans for the orchestra into the next century. Before he went to <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Rattle </PERSON> was the No. 2 conductor with the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philharmonic </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scottish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symphony </ORGANIZATION> and did a lot of guest conducting. `` In some ways,'' he says, `` I was following a more conventional career pattern than I seem to be now.'' Rattle is not without his fans in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In the words of critic <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Porter </PERSON> in the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yorker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Rattle </PERSON> is considered a first-rate conductor who `` inspires players and elates audiences.'' Just before Rattle conducted the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Philharmonic </LOCATION> in his 1985 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> debut, critic <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON> wrote in The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Times: `` The biggest surprise about this debut by the most brilliantly successful conductor of the younger generation in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> _ the perception, power and clarity of whose work has been acclaimed internationally _ is not the age at which it is occurring but the fact that it did not happen long ago. Mr. Rattle has been invited to the Metropolitan Opera and he has been invited to the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Philharmonic </LOCATION>. He has turned both down.'' During a recent stopover in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Rattle </PERSON> was asked if an offer from a prestigious orchestra would lure him away from <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>. `` I've been given enough offers that have n't,'' he answers, declining to elaborate. It is known that in 1984 he rejected an invitation from the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philharmonic </ORGANIZATION> to become its music director. `` The work in <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> is so satisfying,'' he says. `` And it is also unfinished. Now we're planning a festival. Starting in 1991, we'll do spring festivals, each year concentrating on the music of one decade of 20th century music. `` In 2000 we'll just about have caught up with ourselves. In 1999, when we're dealing with the music of the'90s, we will surely be playing music by people who now are schoolchildren.'' <PERSON> Rattle </PERSON> said in 1985 that he thought the <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> Symphony could become the best in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. `` I think they're well on the way,'' he says now. `` My wife tells me I always refer to the City of <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Symphony </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orchestra </LOCATION> as ` us,' which is true,'' he says. `` We consider that we've been able to grow together. They play beautifully as a unit. There's a degree of listening to each other as an ensemble, like chamber music playing, that is unique in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>.'' Though he has made a lot of music documentaries for television, surveying trends or about a particular composer's work, <PERSON> Rattle </PERSON> says he is n't a TV `` natural'' like <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Previn </PERSON>. `` Andre created an extraordinary new audience in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> for music. He can talk to the camera as though it was his best friend. It's something I admire enormously. I ca n't do that.'' Rattle's father briefly led a jazz band. While he appreciates jazz, the younger <PERSON> Rattle </PERSON> knew from the time he entered the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Music </ORGANIZATION> at age 16 that he would conduct. He thought he'd have to be an instrumentalist _ he was a percussionist _ first, whose conducting career would only be beginning `` about now. Conducting happened sooner because <PERSON> Rattle </PERSON> won a conetst. `` I went in simply because if you got in the final 10, there was a chance to work with the <ORGANIZATION> Bournemouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symphony </ORGANIZATION>,'' he says. `` I was 19 and I'd never conducted a professional orchestra. `` I still think I only won because it never occurred to me that I might win and I had no anxiety. The final piece I conducted was <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON>' ` <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Juan </PERSON>,' which takes 17 minutes. There were 20 minutes to rehearse it. At that age, it was probably just as well. I did n't have time to get up the noses of the musicians. Studying conducting, <PERSON> Rattle </PERSON> says, he learned that `` there's as much connection with what your baton does to the orchestra as to what a violinist's bow does to the strings. All motions a conductor makes affect the orchestra, even if you do n't want them to. `` The reason a conductor begins to get halfway competent around 50 or 60 is that he probably has had as much time in front of an orchestra then as the average 20-year-old violinist has had playing his instrument. `` At a certain point, to be able to communicate what you know, you have to know your musicians. That's the reason I went down the road of working very hard with one orchestra.'' One of the reasons Rattle limits his guest conducting is that he and his American wife, soprano <PERSON> Elise </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, and 4-year-old son <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>, known as <PERSON> Sasha </PERSON>, like to spend time together. `` I'm not one of those musicians who wants to live a life which is entirely the musician part,'' he says. `` I'd like to be able to explore the richness of life. There is enough else going on in the world to put music in perspective.''
</TEXT>
