<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 27</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the time came for President <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>'s secretary of war to point out Gen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s route into <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, he had to seek help from a private `` We were filming a scene and we could n't find the place on the map,'' says <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Waterston </PERSON>, who portrays <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> in the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> miniseries `` <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Vidal </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>.'' `` The only person who knew the route was a private.'' The private was one of the Civil War re-enactors who served as Union and Confederate soldiers for the four-hour adaptation of <PERSON> Vidal </PERSON>'s book about life inside the White House. ` They were just an enormous resource in helping the rest of us, who were just pretending, to feel authentic,'' says <PERSON> Waterston </PERSON>. `` I remember riding down a street and there were small groups of Union soldiers along the way. They came to attention as I passed. They did it according to Civil War drill. `` They were immensely supportive of the rest of us. They saved us more than once when we needed information, like with <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s route. `` Lincoln,'' which will be televised on Sunday and Monday, also stars <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> as <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Houseman </PERSON> as Gen. <PERSON> Winfield </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulligan </PERSON> as Secretary of State <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Seward </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McMartin </PERSON> as <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Salmon </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chase </PERSON>, who hopes to become president, and <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Adair </PERSON> as <PERSON> Chase </PERSON>'s overly ambitious daughter, <PERSON> Kate </PERSON>. In an ironic twist on history, the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> scenes were filmed in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, the capital of the Confederacy. The Confederate Home for Needy Women, built as a replica of the original <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, was used as the executive mansion. <PERSON> Petersburg </PERSON>, where <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> put up his last defense before surrendering at <LOCATION> Appomattox </LOCATION>, was also used for some <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> scenes. `` The side benefit of that was that everyone had an enormous interest in the Civil War,'' <PERSON> Waterston </PERSON> says. `` One man came up to me and said, ` If you were the man you're pretending to be I'd want to shoot you.' We got into quite a discussion.'' <PERSON> Waterston </PERSON> says he had not seen any <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> portrayals in a long time and had purposely avoided looking at any. `` <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Fonda </PERSON> seems to me to be the closest to what I imagine he was really like,'' <PERSON> Waterston </PERSON> says. <PERSON> Fonda </PERSON> appeared in `` Young Mr. <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>'' in 1939. `` But I did n't see anything. The danger is that you'll be influenced. In college a friend was doing ` <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>' and made the fatal mistake of seeing <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON>'s film about five days before we opened He could n't put it out of his head.'' <PERSON> Waterston </PERSON> says he read a lot of books on <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>, including one by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Safire </PERSON>, one-time speech writer for President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>. `` If <PERSON> Safire </PERSON> meddles with the facts, he tells you how,'' <PERSON> Waterston </PERSON> says. `` If he's interpreting, he tells you the opposing views so you do n't have to read 17 different books to get all the viewpoints.'' <PERSON> Waterston </PERSON> says when he read <PERSON> Vidal </PERSON>'s book he thought it would make good television. `` It's the Civil War as seen from the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, which is different from the usual way of looking in from the outside. It shows how <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> responded to the pressure of events. I think what's most extraordinary was that he was not perfectly attuned to every situation. `` But when the chips were down he was up to the occasion. That's what people have found remarkable about him _ how could a man of his background find the skills to manage a war on a scale that no one had ever imagined His law partner once described him as a man who read less and thought more than anyone he had ever known.'' <PERSON> Waterston </PERSON> also spent time trying to understand the man. `` <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON> called him ` the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> gorilla,''' he says. `` It certainly takes a breadth of mind to hire that same man as your secretary of war.'' <PERSON> Waterston </PERSON>, who is somewhat Lincolnesque in build and looks, says he has wanted to portray <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> for a long time. `` There ought to be some reward for looking like this,'' he says. `` I thought he was a fascinating man. You ca n't help but be in awe of this combination of high principle and amazing public skills.'' It was <PERSON> Waterston </PERSON>'s third opportunity to work with <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>. Previously, they were in `` Finnegan Begin Again'' and `` Just Between Friends.'' He says he found her portrayal of Mrs. <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> as a woman on the edge `` very bold and interesting.'' <PERSON> Waterson </PE