<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 27</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Carole </PERSON> <PERSON> Shorenstein </PERSON> <PERSON> Hays </PERSON> put her own money, some $ 850,000, where her convictions were and brought `` Fences'' to <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> awards, a Pulitzer Prize and a lucrative film sale were her reward. Smart money was against the play, <PERSON> Hays </PERSON>' first solo producing venture. `` Listen kid, it ai n't commercial,'' <PERSON> Hays </PERSON> deadpans, mimicking the advice she got from seasoned theater professionals. They cautioned against bringing to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the August <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> drama about the upheavals of a black family during the late 1950s. `` It was important for me to do ` Fences' because I believed in it,'' the producer said the other day, between coos to her infant son, <PERSON> Wally </PERSON>, in a Fifth Avenue hotel suite. `` It was very important for me to send out the word to young emerging American playwrights that Broadway is a place where their dreams could be fulfilled. You do n't have to go to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>.'' Besides `` Fences,'' <PERSON> Wally </PERSON>, born Aug. 16, was <PERSON> Hays </PERSON>' other big production last year. When <PERSON> Hays </PERSON>, wearing a maternity evening gown, clambered to the stage of the Mark Hellinger Theater last June to accept a <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> as producer of the best play of the season, she exclaimed, `` I think I'm going to give birth right now.'' She did n't. Little <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hays </PERSON> actually arrived some two months later, but, according to <PERSON> Hays </PERSON>, `` He knows ` Fences' inside and out.'' The baby made his Broadway stage debut _ at age 8 weeks _ in the show. Wrapped in a blanket, he was carried on stage by <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, who usually cradles a doll. <PERSON> Wally </PERSON> had to be kept covered, though. He was playing a little black girl. `` I do n't believe I did that,'' <PERSON> Hays </PERSON> laughs. `` I'm a real stage mother.'' <PERSON> Hays </PERSON> first saw `` Fences'' in January 1986 at <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s Goodman Theater, while it was making the circuit of various regional theaters. By intermission, she knew she wanted to produce the play. She met with director <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON>, who had first done the show at the <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Repertory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, with author <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>. `` It was all very simple,'' she recalls. `` I said, ` I want to do this. It will be done. I have a theater in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>.''' <PERSON> Hays </PERSON> actually runs three theaters there _ the <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>, the Golden Gate and the Orpheum _ all owned by her family. Her father is <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shorenstein </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> real estate mogul. Three years ago, <ORGANIZATION> Forbes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> estimated the family fortune at some $ 300 million. <PERSON> Hays </PERSON> always was stage-struck. Theater-going was the big family activity. She remembers as a child putting on her party dress and white gloves and going to the theater. When her family got into theater real estate, <PERSON> Hays </PERSON> got into the theater business. `` I started at the bottom of the top,'' she recalls, learning what it takes to put on a play. Until `` Fences,'' though, she had never produced a show on her own. `` I think the easiest thing is to find other investors,'' <PERSON> Hays </PERSON> says. `` You can twist arms. I always sold the most Camp Fire Girl cookies and Girl Scout cookies. `` That's the point of my being ` Fence's' sole investor. It was about doing it right and having that control. I think when you produce you must be a benevolent dictator. You must have the power to make a decision, to say ` no' or ` yes.''' Before <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hays </PERSON> staged `` Fences'' at one of her theaters in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and the reviews were mixed. Changes needed to be made, particularly in clarifying the play's final scene, and <PERSON> Hays </PERSON> saw that they were. `` It was a tryout and we went through the process of trying different things,'' she recalls. `` Ultimately, it worked, but it could have gone the other way.'' Now the future of `` Fences'' seems secure. The play, now starring <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dee </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, has started its second year at Broadway's 46th Street Theater. Its fortunes were boosted last April after the drama won the Pulitzer Prize, last June when it won four <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> awards and then later in the year when <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> paid some $ 500,000 for the film rights as a possible vehicle for the super hot <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>. `` I never did the play strictly as a commercial venture,'' <PERSON> Hays </PERSON> says. `` I'm a Broadway baby. I believe in Broadway as being the pinnacle of American theater. `` The first day of rehearsals for ` Fences' I said to everyone, ` We do not know what's going to happen to this play, but we know that we will all do our very, very best,''' she recalls. `` ` And I want all of you to know that as a producer, you have my word that this show is n't going to open and close. No matter what. We're going to try and keep it running.' So far, <PERSON> Hays </PERSON> has n't had any trouble keeping her promise.
