<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Au Revoir Les Enfants,'' ``The Family''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Hollywood's pursuit of the here-and-now has created a glossy, mostly superficial quality to the product coming out of the major studios. Nowadays it's European filmmakers who indulge in remembrance of things past. Two commendable examples are candidates for this year's Academy Award as best foreign language film: `` Au <ORGANIZATION> Revoir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Les </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enfants </ORGANIZATION>'' from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and `` The Family'' from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Malle </PERSON>, after working for a decade in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, returned to his homeland for the most personal film in his distinguished career, `` Au <ORGANIZATION> Revoir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Les </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enfants </ORGANIZATION>'' -LRB- `` Goodbye, Children'' -RRB-. He wrote and directed the film from his own bitter memories as a schoolboy in occupied <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> during World War II. The story begins with a tearful 12-year-old, <PERSON> Julien </PERSON> <PERSON> Quentin </PERSON>, leaving his mother in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> to attend a <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> boys school in <LOCATION> Fontainebleau </LOCATION>. There he encounters the taunts of the older boys, the privations of wartime and the strict discipline of the priests. <PERSON> Julien </PERSON> forms a grudging friendship with a bright, aloof fellow student, <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonnet </PERSON>, whose background is a mystery. <PERSON> Jean </PERSON>, it turns out, is a Jew whose identity is hidden by the sympathetic priests. But <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> is betrayed by someone inside the school, and both he, two other boys and the head priest are taken off to concentration camps. A brief synopsis can not convey the rich texture <PERSON> Malle </PERSON> contributes to the melancholy tale, nor the deep humanity. He is fortunate in his choice of two gifted young performers: <PERSON> Gaspard </PERSON> <PERSON> Manesse </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Julien </PERSON> -RRB- and <PERSON> Raphael </PERSON> <PERSON> Fejto </PERSON> -LRB- Jean -RRB-. In `` The Family,'' <PERSON> Ettore </PERSON> <PERSON> Scola </PERSON> traces the 80-year history of a Roman family through the recollections of the central figure, <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON>. The entire film takes place within the family's apartment, with views of the hallway signifying the change of eras. The turbulent events from 1906 to 1986 provide the backdrop for the family history. The central theme is <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON>'s divided affection between the sister he marries and the sister he really loves. <PERSON> Scola </PERSON> is the master of such wide-sweeping stories, and his depiction of the temperament and humor of the Italians is delightful. He chose three actors to depict <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON> at different ages: young <PERSON> Emmanuele </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamaro </PERSON>, the rising star <PERSON> Andrea </PERSON> <PERSON> Occhipinto </PERSON> as <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON> from 20 to 40, and <PERSON> Vittorio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gassman </PERSON> thereafter. All three are superb. `` Au <ORGANIZATION> Revoir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Les </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enfants </ORGANIZATION>,'' an Orion Classics release, is rated PG and runs 103 minutes. In French with English subtitles. `` The Family'' is a <ORGANIZATION> Vestron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> release, rated PG, running time: 127 minutes. In Italian with English subtitles.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
