<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Animal Fat and Felt Do Sculpture Make</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH JAUTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Beuys </PERSON>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s answer to the late pop artist <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>, once said the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall should be raised 10 centimeters for aesthetic reasons. The comment did little to endear him to his countrymen. For most of his career, <PERSON> Beuys </PERSON> was better known in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> than at home. But now, two years after his death, Germans have suddenly become fans of the avant-garde artist. Prices for his works are skyrocketing. Critics are singing his praises. And record numbers of visitors are flocking to see the first-ever major exhibition of his sketches and sculptures in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> at one of the nation's leading museums. In <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, a smaller exhibit of <PERSON> Beuys </PERSON>' early drawings also is attracting crowds to the communist capital. The overhaul of <PERSON> Beuys </PERSON>' reputation has been speedy. Less than a year ago, cleaners at the <ORGANIZATION> Duesseldorf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> accidentally threw out a Beuys sculpture made of wood, butter and animal fat. The cleaners thought the creation was, literally, garbage. `` I often wonder what <PERSON> Beuys </PERSON> himself would think of all this,'' said a bemused <PERSON> Heiner </PERSON> <PERSON> Bastian </PERSON>, who served as the artist's assistant for 12 years. `` He was used to criticizing society, but not to being toasted by it.'' <PERSON> Beuys </PERSON> specialized in sculptures made out of everyday items or cast-off objects: empty boxes and tin cans, scraps of wood, stones, shoes, blackboards or pieces of furniture. Felt and fat were his favorite materials. In one creation, a single egg sits atop a wooden bench. In another, a pair of battered boots dangles on a string above two empty crates. A 1977 sculpture entitled `` In Memory of My Youth in the Mountains'' consists of three large, white boulders inscribed with the same words of the title. `` <PERSON> Beuys </PERSON> believed art had to be puzzling to be good, and there is no denying that he is puzzling,'' said <PERSON> Bastian </PERSON>, who organized the 120-piece exhibition in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Martin-Gropius-Bau </ORGANIZATION> museum. The 10-week show, which opened Feb. 20, drew an unexpected 9,000 visitors in its first five days, an unofficial record for an exhibit in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. With his jaunty and battered felt hat, vest and rumpled trenchcoat, <PERSON> Beuys </PERSON> never looked like he fit in among the prosperous and serious West Germans. His sense of humor was also atypically German. He was fired from his job as administrator at the <ORGANIZATION> Duesseldorf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> in 1972, after announcing he would hire only applicants who had failed a formal art program. He was dismissed by an angry <PERSON> Johannes </PERSON> <PERSON> Rau </PERSON>, then the economics minister for the state of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rhine-Westphalia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Beuys </PERSON>' birthplace and lifelong home. But <PERSON> Rau </PERSON> and other politicians have since changed their tune. Now the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rhine-Westphalian </LOCATION> governor, <PERSON> Rau </PERSON> traveled to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> last month to open the city's first <PERSON> Beuys </PERSON> exhibition and lavish praise on his former employee. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Volker </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassemer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s culture chief, claimed <PERSON> Beuys </PERSON> for Berliners. `` It is only fitting that the best-known contemporary German artist be shown first in <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Hassemer </PERSON> told reporters at the Bueys exhibit's gala opening. <PERSON> Bastian </PERSON> is at a loss to explain the boost in Bueys' popularity, and says it caught him by surprise. `` Throughout the history of art, there have been artists who have become popular only after their deaths,'' he said. `` That has been particularly true for modern art. No one can say why this is so.'' In a recent issue of <LOCATION> Der </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Spiegel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s largest news weekly, the entire letters column was devoted to <PERSON> Beuys </PERSON>. Opinion was running decidedly against the artist. `` You recently ran pictures of <PERSON> Beuys </PERSON> works,'' wrote <PERSON> Immo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kayser-Eichberg </PERSON>, a lawyer from the town of <LOCATION> Meerbusch </LOCATION>. `` You do not seriously consider these things works of art, do you?'' Visitors to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beuys </LOCATION> exhibition were more tactful. `` No I do not understand it,'' said <PERSON> Ulrike </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagel </PERSON>, gazing at a <PERSON> Beuys </PERSON> object that appeared to be little more than several empty blackboards scattered on the floor. `` But that does not mean I do not automatically dislike it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, March 25-27</NOTE>
