<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` One Mind'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Global </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Lievano </PERSON> <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Lievano </PERSON> gives special thanks to Zen Master <PERSON> Rama </PERSON> on the back of `` One Mind,'' his new record. If you buy this record, you may wish to enlist Mr. <PERSON> Rama </PERSON>'s assistance in learning the patience you'll need to get through it. `` One Mind'' is simple-minded. It starts at the beginning and never wanders far beyond, winding back and forth upon itself with no apparent direction. Lievano plays a variety of instruments, including guitars, synthesizers and drums. He is assisted by <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> on drums, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Kindler </PERSON> on violin and <PERSON> Issac </PERSON> <PERSON> Epps </PERSON> on hand percussion. The musicianship is proficient and the production is excellent. The players turn in a nice riff here or a soft phrase there and, if you like this sort of technical mastery of the soul, the record delivers. For this reviewer, though, the overall effect was less than zero. This record has its roots in the 1970s. It is derivative of <LOCATION> Chick </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Corea </LOCATION>'s `` Return to Forever'' and <PERSON> Kindler </PERSON>'s playing sounds suspiciously like that of <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Luc </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponty </PERSON>, who rocketed out of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in the'70s on a bow and an electric violin and has been laying down the same tracks ever since. With apologies to Mr. <PERSON> Rama </PERSON>, an ancient <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> philospher once said, `` You ca n't step in the same river twice.'' But <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Lievano </PERSON> is sure trying. _ By <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Reindl </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` If My Heart Had Windows'' -LRB- MCA -RRB- _ <PERSON> Patty </PERSON> <PERSON> Loveless </PERSON> <PERSON> Patty </PERSON> <PERSON> Loveless </PERSON>' new album consists of 10 songs, and the writing credit is different on each. But Loveless' singing and the production of <ORGANIZATION> Emory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gordy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jr. </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> make the album into a cohesive set that's as country as grits. `` If My Heart Had Windows'' includes a honky-tonk waltz -LRB- the title cut, by <PERSON> Dallas </PERSON> <PERSON> Frazier </PERSON> -RRB-; country swing -LRB- <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>' `` I Ca n't Get You Off of My Mind'' -RRB-; and plenty of ballads. Loveless' full-throated alto really hits its stride on Side 2, climaxing on <PERSON> John </PERSON> and <PERSON> Johanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>'s `` Fly Away,'' which lives up to its name with a soaring chorus reminiscent of the Halls' defunct pop group, <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> The arrangements, built around the solid rhythm section of <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> <PERSON> Sklar </PERSON> and <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bayers </PERSON>, include such nice touches as a steel and fiddle playing in unison on the break of `` I Ca n't Get You Off of My Mind.'' The material occasionally sags, but most of the album contains strong and honest performances. By <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Wine </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
