<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Fashion:Karan     03-14 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Fashion: Karan,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>FASHION: Karan</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY706</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hand-crocheted knits and the most feminine of stretchy laces are some of the richly textured fabrics <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Karan </PERSON> uses to create her draped and sculpted clothing for spring. The collection is unquestionably one of the most beautiful of the season. The delicate, airy weave of her fabrics _ inspired, Ms. <PERSON> Karan </PERSON> says, by her collection of lacey antique straw hats _ makes her clothing soft and feminine without artificial-looking frills, poufs or trim. `` I want women to feel beautiful in a most luxurious and sophisticated way,'' she says. Ms. <PERSON> Karan </PERSON> does n't design mix-and-match sportswear. A jacket is carefully sculpted to be worn with a certain skirt and camisole to capture the fluid line of a one-piece dress. Long `` scarf jackets'' in navy and cream stretch wool crepe, elegantly draped to one side and gathered there with a satin bow, were worn with soft, fluid <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION> shorts and short skirts. Sometimes there was a hint of a lace decollete, twisted V-neck bodysuit or little camisole. Body-revealing wrapped tops also are a favorite of Ms. <PERSON> Karan </PERSON>'s, and she matched them with flowing navy pajama pants worn with elegant high-heel pumps. Ms. <PERSON> Karan </PERSON>, whose designs concentrate on fabric and shape, used understated solid colors _ navy, cream, taupe and mulberry for daytime, with red replacing mulberry for evening. Gold jewelry and buttons, with the dull shine of family heirlooms, provided a touch of brightness. Her collection easily made the transition from daytime to eveningwear, since the basic shapes of her clothing vary little. But, for evening, her fabrics attained a lustrous quality _ most apparent in her clingy lace sweaters with plunging necklines, worn over soft skirts or tucked in and cinched at the waist with satin bands. Dramatic elegance describes an off-the-shoulder, scoop-neck jacket in stretchy scarlet silk, held in place at the waist by a ribbon rose and then cut away to show a hand-crocheted skirt. The `` scarf jacket,'' with its softly draped fabric at the side, reappeared as a stunning long evening gown in navy.
</TEXT>
