 The demise of the dress-for-success uniform that puts women in box-like suits and little uptight blouses is no surprise to <ORGANIZATION> Alcott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>, which calls itself wardrobers to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s successful women. The specialty store entered the women's apparel market three years ago with the idea that executive women are tired of looking like male clones and want their clothing to be distinguished, but with a soft, feminine touch. `` I think one of the reasons we've been as successful as we have is that we understand this lady is a lady _ she's not a man,'' says <PERSON> Coleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, 39, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Alcott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>. Advertisements for the store's 11 outlets across the country show beautiful, blond women with an impeccably coiffed <PERSON> Grace </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> look. The company's president, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeffries </PERSON>, 43, bristled at the suggestion that his store has something in common with <ORGANIZATION> Brooks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION>. `` They're traditional clothiers. We're in the fashion business,'' he said. For instance, <PERSON> Jeffries </PERSON> notes that <ORGANIZATION> Alcott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> had no hesitations about embracing the short skirt for the fall season. And Ms. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> says customer response has been `` tremendous.'' `` We think the knee is quite stylish, quite appropriate,'' she says. Ninety-eight percent of the stores' merchandise, <PERSON> Jeffries </PERSON> says, is designed by talent inside the company. He and Ms. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> want their apparel to appeal to executive women, `` presidents of country clubs'' and wives of `` very successful men.'' The one common characteristic shared by them all, Ms. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> says, is that they are `` successful.'' The store strives for a refined yet efficient atmosphere. Classical music and antique furniture aim to sooth the harried shopper. Merchandise is grouped in complementary color blocks so a woman can put together a total wardrobe without searching for a blouse or jacket to go with a skirt. And ready to help her in her selections are some of the highest paid salespeople _ called `` wardrobe consultants'' _ in the retail business. `` They can make upwards to $ 50,000 a year. ... And the norm is between $ 20,000 and $ 50,000 a year,'' <PERSON> Jeffries </PERSON> says. `` Our customer is traditionally a hard-working executive woman who does n't have time to wait unattended for sales help or to check out,'' Ms. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> says. <ORGANIZATION> Alcott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> is a privately held company whose 1987 sales are expected to exceed $ 50 million.
