<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>FASHION: Lurie</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The miniskirt may be back, but it's more formal and refined than the thigh-high hemlines of the 1960s, says <PERSON> Alison </PERSON> <PERSON> Lurie </PERSON>, Pulitzer Prize novelist and fashion commentator. The more sophisticated minis, she says, may be an expression of women's confidence at work and in the economy. `` When things are good economically, skirts tend to go up. If we're happy and carefree, we begin to act and dress like children. The miniskirt is part of this general phenomenon,'' she says. `` When we were young, we wore very short skirts; children still do. But there's an age beyond which you have to be in absolutely wonderful shape to wear a miniskirt, maybe 40.'' <PERSON> Lurie </PERSON> won the fiction Pulitzer Prize in 1985 for the novel `` Foreign Affairs'' and also wrote `` The War Between the Tates.'' She is an English professor at <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> here in narrative writing, folklore and children's literature. A native of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, she was raised in <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, and is the mother of three grown sons. She is also the author of `` The Language of Clothes,'' written in 1981, in which she said that the lacy, baby-doll style of the 1960s made `` grown women look like toddlers with a glandular affliction, or like severely retarded nubile teen-agers.'' The miniskirts, she said, seemed `` ridiculous rather than seductive.'' In the beginning, `` it was said that men would n't be able to concentrate on their work if they had ` beautiful chicks' running around in brightly colored clothes,'' she says. `` Women had to scrape their hair back into buns and wear dark, depressing clothes that hid the figure. `` Those clothes were boring. Women are not used to wearing the same thing every day the way men are; they could n't put up with it. Now that they are confident in their jobs, they can kick up their heels a little and stop wearing such a dreary costume.'' It was consumer demand, not designer contrivance, that brought the miniskirt back, she says, noting that so far the skirts seem more popular away from work than at the office.
</TEXT>
