<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wholesale prices dipped 0.2 percent in Feburary as both energy and food costs declined, including a dramatic 70 percent tumble in the price of lettuce, the government said. The decline reported Friday in the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Producer Price Index partially erased a 0.4 percent increase in January. Analysts said it provided further evidence that inflation remains tame. The producer index does not show two categories in which price increases have been the most pronounced _ services and imported goods.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government said retail sales edged up 0.6 percent in February, bolstered by strong demand for autos, but economists worried that sales in January were much weaker than previously believed. Instead of a 0.5 percent rise in sales, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday sales actually fell 0.2 percent during January, showing the consumer sector is weaker than previously believed.
</TEXT>
