<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s 5-week-old `` collar'' on computerized trading appears to be an effective therapy for easing volatility in the post-crash market and luring back frightened investors, analysts say. But the restriction also makes the market less attractive to investors who thrive on risk, which could theoretically drive them overseas. Some market experts argue that the restriction would do little to squelch another panic.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
