<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     03-14 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down As Pound Surges On; Gold Firmer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar fell against all major currencies in early European trading today as the British pound continued a weeklong surge with the Conservative government split on whether to rein in sterling. Gold prices rose. Some traders said the pound was helping to depress the dollar. The pound jumped more than half a cent to $ 1.8590, compared with $ 1.8535 late Friday. The pound has risen 8 cents from a week ago. Sterling has been rising on expectations the government will announce substantial tax cuts in its annual spring budget Tuesday, and was boosted further by the government split. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> last week rejected state intervention to depress the pound, either by selling sterling or lowering interest rates _ thus overruling Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>. A strong pound hurts British exports. But Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> believes lowering interest rates to make the pound less attractive to foreign investors will encourage borrowing and fuel inflation. After years of low-deficit budgets, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is heading for a balanced budget, or even a surplus of revenue over expenditure, for the first time in nearly 20 years. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar closed at 127.23 yen, down 0.57 yen from Friday. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> the dollar slipped further to 126.55 yen. <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> dealers said the dollar was depressed partly by pessimistic expectations for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> January trade figures to be released Thursday. Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Friday's rates, included: 1.6575 West German marks, down from 1.6615; 1.3665 Swiss francs, down from 1.3720; 5.6325 French francs, down from 5.6515; 1.8624 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8680; 1.228.40 Italian lire, down from 1.232.55; and 1.2552 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2553 Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 441.80 a troy ounce, compared with late Friday's $ 440.50. At mid-morning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 441.90. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the noon bid price was $ 441.85 dollars, up from $ 441 late Friday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold closed at a $ 444.81 bid, up $ 1.27 from Saturday's closing price. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on Monday at a bid price of $ 6.23 a troy ounce, down from $ 6.36 late Friday.
