<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> says it will not launch a special study of a widely used herbicide suspected of causing cancer among farmers because other research has not confirmed the suspicion. A major commercial user, however, said it wo n't put the chemical back in its lineup until the cancer picture is clarified, and a scientist with an environmental group called the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s decision `` outrageous.'' The herbicide is 2,4-D, short for dichlorophenoxyacetic acid. A 1986 study said it was the fourth most widely used pesticide in the nation, with more than 39 million pounds of active ingredient sold the previous year. The great bulk of that is believed to be used for broadleaf weed control in wheat fields, though 2,4-D also is widely used on highway rights of way, on lawns and in forests. Following several scientific reports associating certain cancers with farming or exposure to various _ and sometimes unspecified _ herbicides, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 found that farmers in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> who used 2,4-D more than 20 times a year, mixing their own formulations, had an eight times greater chance than normal of getting a specific cancer called non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, a cancer of the lymph system. Home and garden users did not face concentrations large enough to cause concern, the study said. The herbicide aroused suspicion because it can be contaminated with small amounts of chemicals related to the dioxins, though there are no <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> reports, and only one abroad, of contamination with the most toxic form of dioxin. The contaminants of 2,4-D generally have only about 1 percent of the cancer-causing power of the most toxic dioxin. In all the controversy over dioxin, a cancer called soft-tissue sarcoma has been at the center of the issue _ and this cancer sometimes was found in the early 2,4-D reports. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> frequently puts suspicious pesticides into what it calls `` special review,'' a way of bringing the chemical to the head of the line. The agency may call for additional studies by the manufacturer and the reviews may end up with new use restrictions or an outright ban. In this case, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has decided not to begin such a review. Spokesman <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Heier </PERSON> confirmed trade press reports of the decision, describing the decision as a `` tough call.'' Animal studies, he said, `` do not suggest that it's a carcinogen,'' and `` I think there are quite a few -LRB- human -RRB- epidemiology studies'' that also fail to confirm the cancer-causing ability of 2,4-D. It is extremely rare for a chemical to cause cancer in humans but not in laboratory animals. The best example is arsenic. Officials to whom <PERSON> Heier </PERSON> referred more detailed questions did not immediately return telephone calls. The agency plans a news conference on Thursday to discuss its decision. One study of farm and forest workers in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> found elevated incidence of non-Hodgkins lymphoma and another cancer called multiple myeloma, but did not examine exposure to pesticides. A followup study, however, found no excess risk of cancer as a result of exposure to chemicals of the 2,4-D class. <ORGANIZATION> Chemlawn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> stopped using 2,4-D after the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> results were announced. The company acted `` out of concern for our employees,'' of whom 2,500 to 3,000 probably were using 2,4-D on 80 days a year, said spokesman <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardymon </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. It has arranged a study of employees by the institute, and will not decide whether to resume use of 2,4-D until results are reported, probably late next year, though <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s decision `` probably is right,'' said <PERSON> Hardymon </PERSON>. `` I think it's outrageous,'' <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON>, staff scientist of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Against </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Misuse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pesticides </ORGANIZATION>, said of the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s decision. She was particularly critical of the weight given to animal studies that showed no effect. `` We only do animal studies when we do n't have human studies,'' but in this case a good study of humans _ the <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> farmers _ was outweighed by animal studies, she said. She said `` 2,4,5-T was banned mostly because of birth defects -LRB- among humans -RRB- in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> ... and that is not anywhere near as hard to refute as the study <ORGANIZATION> NCI </ORGANIZATION> did.''
