<HEAD>Rig Count Drops By 32 To Total 946</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of oil and gas rigs working in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> decreased by 32 this week to total 946, <ORGANIZATION> Baker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> announced. The total reflects the number of rigs actively exploring for oil as of last Friday, not the number rigs producing oil. The previous week, the count had decreased by five to 978. `` In a normal year, the low comes in late March or early April, and then begins a gradual increase from that point,'' said <PERSON> Ike </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerridge </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> economist who compiles the count. `` It is not unusual for it to be coming down in March.'' <PERSON> Kerridge </PERSON> said companies usually accelerate their exploration spending as the year progresses. A year ago, the rig count stood at 761, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> said. Houston-based <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, an oil toolmaker, tallies the number of working rigs and the count is the widely-watched industry index of drilling activity. <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tool </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which merged this year with <ORGANIZATION> Baker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, has kept track of the number of working rigs since 1940. The rig count reached a peak of 4,500 active rigs in December 1981 _ the height of the oil boom. But as oil prices plunged to less than $ 10 per 42-gallon barrel in the summer of 1986, the count fell to 663, the lowest since <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> began compiling figures. Among the major oil producing states, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> lost 14 rigs, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> lost seven, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> lost five, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> each lost three, and <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> lost one apiece. <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> gained three rigs, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> gained two and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> gained one. The states of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> showed no change.
