<FIRST>r f BC-Unemployment     03-14 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Unemployment,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Billion New Jobs by 2030 Would Provide Full Employment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Close to two billion new jobs would have to be created by 2030 if the goal of full employment were to be attained worldwide, according to a survey published Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>. Citing data from the <ORGANIZATION> ILO </ORGANIZATION>'s new statistical yearbook, the survey suggested that this goal was out of reach at current levels of creating new employment. It said that globally an average 47 million new jobs are needed each year over the next four decades to cope with the population growth and absorb the `` armies of unemployed and underemployed.'' The yearbook, covering data from almost 100 nations, said women and young people continue to fare worst, but that the women's share of the workforce increased in many parts of the world. However, in some developed countries, including <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, jobless rates of women were more than double than those of men. The picture looked grimmest for young people. In <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, more than half of all teenagers and almost half of those between 20 and 25 were unmployed in 1986, and in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> the rates were 27.5 and 16 percent. No statistics were available for African countries where the problem is believed to be most serious in the Third World. The statistics list a decline of unemployment in 31 countries between 1985 and 1986. Improvement was most marked in Latin American and <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> countries although they still have some of the highest unemployment rates in the world. Rates dropped from 12.1 percent to 8.7 percent in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>; from 21.8 percent to 18.9 percent in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>; from 11.8 percent to 8.2 percent in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>; and from 14 percent to 10.3 percent in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. The trend was also downward in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, from 7.1 to 6.9 percent. The hardest hit European country was <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, but the rate also declined slightly from 21.9 percent to 21.5 percent. By contrast, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s rate was up from 17.8 percent to 18.2 percent. <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, with a rate of 0.8 percent, ranked at the bottom of the survey. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, at 2 percent, and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, at 2.8 percent, also reported almost full employment.
</TEXT>
