 <ORGANIZATION> Moore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McCormack </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Monday its board rejected as inadequate a sweetened $ 450 million bid from <ORGANIZATION> Southdown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and authorized the sale of a <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON> subsidiary as a move to enchance shareholder value. Last week <ORGANIZATION> Southdown </ORGANIZATION>, a Houston-based cement and energy company, increased its tender offer for all of <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON>'s outstanding common stock to $ 35 per share from its previous offer of $ 31 per share. The initial offer valued the company at about $ 391 million. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON> called the latest bid `` inadequate and not in the best interests'' of the company and its shareholders. `` The board of directors of <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON> continues to believe that remaining independent would be a superior alternative over the long-range term,'' the company said in a statement. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON>'s board authorized the sale of <ORGANIZATION> Moore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McCormack </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the company's oil and gas subsidiary. The company said it is `` continuing to explore and investigate the variety of ... transactions intended to enhance securityholder values, other than a significant acquisition by the company.'' <ORGANIZATION> Southdown </ORGANIZATION> said its tender offer was conditional upon the valid tender of a majority of <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON> common stock, the invalidation of <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON>'s `` poison pill'' anti-takeover defense and the acquisition of sufficient financing. <ORGANIZATION> Southdown </ORGANIZATION> produces and sells cement and ready-mixed concrete and is active in oil and gas production. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, produces building materials and is involved in oil and gas exploration and production, mainly in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>.
