<HEAD>Documents: Company May Have Misled Doctors About IUD</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new 2nd graf on stock market reaction.</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: a version on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Internal documents indicate that <ORGANIZATION> G.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Searle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> may have misled doctors and a federal regulatory agency about safety characteristics of its Copper-7 contraceptive, according to an attorney representing a woman who claims the device made her sterile. Wall Street reacted Monday by knocking the stock of <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Searle </ORGANIZATION>'s parent, down $ 3.12 -LCB- a share to $ 83.37 -LCB-. According to the documents, <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> apparently hid complaints about the Copper-7 from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, the attorney said. An <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> task force recommended that a federal grand jury investigate whether any laws were broken by <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>'s allegedly misleading reports on animal studies for a number of products, including the Copper-7. No charges were filed. The Searle documents, produced for a trial set to start May 16 in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION>, became public last week on order of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Renner </PERSON>. The judge rejected <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>'s arguments that the memorandums be kept confidential to protect trade secrets. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Ciresi </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> attorney who represent <PERSON> Esther </PERSON> <PERSON> Kociemba </PERSON>, a Melrose woman who claims to have been made infertile by the Copper-7, said: `` These documents can be characterized as the tip of the iceberg. Once all the documents are disclosed -LRB- to the public -RRB-, they will collectively establish without a doubt that the Copper-7 causes -LRB- infection -RRB- and <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> knew about it, but did not disclose it to doctors or to women.'' Nationally, there have been 17 trials involving <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>'s Copper-7, 14 of them decided in the company's favor <PERSON> Kociemba </PERSON>'s case `` will be the first case tried against <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> where the jury will be presented with evidence from <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>'s files showing what <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> knew about the hazards of the IUD, when they knew about them and what they did about them _ which was to conceal the information,'' <PERSON> Ciresi </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Strain </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, an attorney for <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>, said, `` We are confident when a jury hears all the evidence, reviews all the documents and, most importantly, hears from the doctors that they will conclude the Copper-7 is a good IUD that does not cause infection.'' He said that documents not yet released and defense testimony will show that the company did not mislead anyone. A major issue in the suit will be whether the Copper-7 tail string was a single strand of polypropylene incapable of transporting infection-causing bacteria into the uterus, as <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> contends, or if it was made up of many tiny strands that could act as a tunnel for bacteria, as <PERSON> Ciresi </PERSON> contends. One of the Searle documents quotes a company official saying for the first time that the Copper-7 string is a `` bundle of fused micro-filaments.'' The Copper-7 was a popular intrauterine device from 1974 to 1988, when <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> withdrew it from the market citing litigation costs. Many <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> women continue to use Copper-7 IUDs and <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> recently resumed manufacturing the device in order to fill foreign orders.
