<HEAD>Dollar Mixed; Gold Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar turned in a mixed performance against other major currencies Monday as traders bided their time in advance of Thursday's report on the January merchandise trade deficit. Gold prices edged higher. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> said gold was bid at $ 441.90 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up from $ 441.25 an ounce late Friday. Traders in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> said the dollar's immediate future was closely tied to the British pound, which has gained 10 cents against the dollar in the past month. Traders were cautious about the dollar-sterling rate on the eve of Tuesday's British budget statement. Also in the offing were a <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report Tuesday on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' fourth-quarter balance in the current account, the broadest measure of trade, and Thursday's merchandise trade figures. Currency traders in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> have largely been reacting to developments overseas in the last two weeks, ever since the big run-up in the British pound, said <PERSON> Keiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Udagawa </PERSON>, chief trader for the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` Now it's going to be a calm before the storm, before the trade figures,'' said <PERSON> Zlatko </PERSON> <PERSON> Glamuzina </PERSON>, chief currency dealer for the <ORGANIZATION> Banco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> di </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sicilia </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound edged upward to $ 1.8575 from $ 1.8535 Friday. But later in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the pound finished the trading day at $ 1.8540, down from $ 1.8562 late Friday. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> the dollar closed at 127.23 Japanese yen, down from 127.80 on Friday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> the dollar traded at 126.85 yen. At the end of the trading day in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar sank to 126.79 yen from 127.29 yen late Friday. Other late rates for the dollar in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with Friday's late rates, included: 1.6629 West German marks, up from 1.6602; 1.3717 Swiss francs, up from 1.3696; 1.2572 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2571; 5.6395 French francs, down from 5.6460; and 1,231.25 Italian lire, up from 1,231. Other late rates for the dollar in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with Friday's late rates, included: 1.6645 West German marks, up from 1.6615; 1.3693 Swiss francs, down from 1.3720; 5.6375 French francs, down from 5.6515; 1.8645 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8680; 1,227.87 Italian lire, down from 1,232.55; and 1.2577 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2553. Gold bullion prices gained about 50 cents in light trading. The late gold price in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the major <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> center, was $ 441 a troy ounce bid, up from $ 440.50 late Friday. The late <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> bid price was $ 441.50, up from $ 441. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery rose 60 cents a troy ounce to $ 441.90 an ounce. Earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> gold closed at $ 444.81 bid, up from $ 443.54. Silver bullion traded late in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at $ 6.22 bid a troy ounce, down from $ 6.36. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver bullion for current delivery rose 6.2 cents to $ 6.240 an ounce.
