<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investor <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Abboud </PERSON> said Monday he is confident debt holders of <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bancorporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> will surrender their notes to the bank for less than face value. On March 4, more than 71 percent of the Houston-based bank holding company's 37 million shareholders approved a $ 1.5 billion federal bailout plan. The plan _ which would be the second largest government bank bailout _ calls for $ 970 million in federal assistance, a $ 500 million infusion of capital raised privately by an investor group headed by <PERSON> Abboud </PERSON>, and a spinoff of $ 1.79 billion in book value of poorly performing assets. First City, the fourth-largest bank firm in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, grew quickly during the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> oil boom, but was hammered by energy and real estate losses when oil prices plummeted. For 1987, the company posted a $ 1.1 billion loss. Under a buyout plan that was made a condition of the bailout, holders of <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION>'s debt securities would be paid less than the face value of their notes, said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON>, director of communications for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The amounts offered to note holders ranged from 35 cents to 45 cents on the dollar, he said. But <PERSON> Abboud </PERSON>, who would head the bank under the plan, told federal regulators in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> this weekend that not enough of the note holders have agreed to sell at those prices. The agreement provides that 90 percent of the debt holders turn over their notes by a 4 p.m. CST Tuesday deadline. During a Monday afternoon news conference in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Abboud </PERSON> would not say how many debt holders had submitted their notes, but expressed confidence the deal can be closed by month's end. `` There's a high degree of confidence and enthusiasm as presently structured,'' said <PERSON> Abboud </PERSON>, who was wearing a `` Yes We Can! First City'' button on his lapel. `` I would ask the other debt holders who have not yet tendered to cooperate with us and submit their securities. We're prepared to close if conditions are fully satisfied,'' he added. <PERSON> Abboud </PERSON> said debt holders are getting more than if the bank were liquidated. `` The offer on the table is basically the offer until Tuesday afternoon,'' he said. `` There is no intent on anybody's part to make any material changes in the monetary terms of the offering.'' Last week, First City bonds were trading well above the prices being offered under the bailout plan. Analysts said this indicated that some investors were gambling that federal regulators would come up with a higher price for the First City debt. The investors are betting that the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION>, in its eagerness to wrap up the <LOCATION> First </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> deal, will either sweeten the offer or reduce the percentage of shares that need to be tendered. Still other analysts said last week that the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> could refuse to raise the offer for fear of setting a precedent for future bank bailouts. Other options available to the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION>, the analysts said, include canceling the <PERSON> Abboud </PERSON> deal and reopening bidding for the bank, or a move by the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> to itself take over <LOCATION> First </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, as it did with <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGA