<HEAD>Contintenal Cited For Tying IRS Plan to Flying Their Skies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> advertisement designed to catch readers' attention has caught some flak from the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> Consumer Affairs Department. The department said Monday it had cited the airline for a March 10 ad in the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> that it claims gave the false impression that the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> was involved with the airline's promotion. The ad in question stated: `` Fly <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> to be out of the country on April 15 and the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> will allow you an automatic filing extension.'' <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> <PERSON> Aponte </PERSON>, commissioner of Consumer Affairs, said the ad falsely implied a sponsorship by the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> and falsely asserted that consumers must leave the country in order to get the automatic extension to file. <PERSON> Aponte </PERSON> also said the ad failed to give important information concerning the filing of extensions. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON>, a spokesman at <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> headquarters, said an <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> official indicated last week there were no problems with the ad and that it was straightforward and accurate. `` We're mostly very puzzled that the department would insinuate itself into an issue where there is no argument,'' <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> has stated that it has no problems whatsoever with the advertisement.'' <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, a spokesman for the consumer affairs department, said <ORGANIZATION